<DOCNO> AP900801-0005 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
new york air traffic controllers declared a fuel 
emergency aboard an avianca jet from colombia after the pilot said 
he only had 15 minutes of fuel a federal aviation administration 
spokeswoman said wednesday 
the tuesday night incident was a chilling reminder of januarys 
avianca flight 52 which crashed into a hillside in cove neck long 
island killing 73 people on board after it ran out of fuel en 
route to kennedy international airport 
air traffic controllers declared a fuel emergency tuesday on 
board avianca flight 20 also heading for kennedy airport 
controllers made the declaration after they detected some 
reluctance by the planes pilot to call a fuel emergency according 
to joseph fuscella an air traffic controller 
the controllers immediately put all other planes in the area on 
hold and gave the 767 jetliner a straightin pattern to kennedy 
where it landed safely at 924 pm said diane spitaliere the faa 
spokeswoman 
the jet reportedly had only 5 minutes of fuel left on board when 
it landed according to fuscella and spitaliere 
spitaliere said that the faa is looking into the incident 
fuscella said avianca 20 en route from cali and bogota had 
followed the same flight path up the east coast as flight 52 
flight 20 apparently was placed in an undetermined holding 
pattern in the washington area 
the incident developed about 30 miles south of kennedy airport 
when the pilot told new york regional controllers he had only 15 
minutes of fuel left 
the air traffic controllers alerted controllers at the local 
control station known as tracon or new york terminal radar 
control based in garden city on long island 
there was some confusion as to whether the pilot had said 15 
minutes or 51 minutes said fuscella 
tracon controllers contacted the pilot who confirmed that he 
had only 15 minutes of fuel on board 
he was asked if he wanted to declare a fuel emergency said 
fuscella 
when they detected some reluctance in his voice the 
controllers mindful of the avianca crash decided to declare an 
emergency and bring him right in said fuscella 
avianca flight 52 crashed after being placed in holding patterns 
for 90 minutes the crew apparently failed to properly alert 
controllers of a fuel emergency 
if an emrgency hadnt been declared tuesday the plane would 
have been instructed to take its position at the end of a line of 
aircraft waiting in a pattern to land at kennedy 
the final landing flight then would have taken approximately 25 
minutes according to fuscella 
by putting flight 20 at the head of the line it took the plane 
12 minutes to land he said 
fuscella said there were numerous planes in a holding pattern 
tuesday because of severe thunderstorms in the area and normal 
evening congestion 
the flight scheduled to land at 824 pm was an hour late but 
it was not clear where the delay occurred or what caused it 
the controllers proceeded on the side of caution in light of 
the other crash said spitaliere 
fuscella agreed saying this certainly was a deja vu 
situation 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

