<TEXT>
the new director of a bulgarian weapons company 
whose arms have been linked to terrorists plans to share 
information with western governments the new york times reported 
the newly appointed general director of the kintex arms company 
anton saldjiski said an interview published in the papers 
thursday editions that the company had records of all weapons and 
ammunition exported to warsaw pact nations and to countries like 
libya syria and iraq 
some of these nations are suspected by western governments of 
having transferred arms to the palestinian liberation organization 
the irish reublican army and other groups 
if western governments obtain weapons used by terrorists and 
trace them to bulgaria kintex will tell them what country the arms 
were orginally shipped to saldjiski said 
he said kintex had just joined interpol the international law 
enforcement group 
he said kintexs customers must sign contracts stipulating that 
they wont deliver the weapons to a third country 
to my knowledge we have not been involved in the direct supply 
of arms to terrorists but it is possible that these arms have 
reached such groups via governments we have supplied legally he 
said 
he said he had been told that kintex equipment has reached the 
plo 
kintex was linked by some investigators to the 1981 
assassination attempt on pope john paul ii 
</TEXT>
