<TEXT>
eugene l roberts jr who led the 
philadelphia inquirer to 17 pulitzer prizes in 16 years announced 
tuesday he would retire as executive editor and president effective 
sept 1 
he will be succeeded by maxwell ep king an inquirer editor 
for 15 years before his promotion in 1987 to vice president for 
consumer marketing and distribution the changes were announced by 
robert j hall chairman and publisher 
roberts 58 joined the knightridder newspaper in 1972 he told 
the staff tuesday afternoon that he had at one time talked of 
retiring at 55 
but then when 55 came there were family responsibilities that 
made it seem the wrong time he said now the time has come 
ive been here in this job for 18 years and thats a long time 
roberts will remain with the knightridder newspaper group as a 
consultant and said he plans to enter discussions at the end of the 
week about a university teaching position 
king 46 became a senior vice president in 1988 his title will 
be editor of the inquirer and executive vice president of 
philadelphia newspapers inc 
an awardwinning journalist and son of a weekly newspaper 
editor roberts joined the inquirer in 1972 
roberts covered the civil rights movement in the 1960s and the 
vietnam war for the new york times and later became its national 
editor 
he began his career as a farm reporter for the goldsboro nc 
newsargus he also worked at the virginianpilot of norfolk va 
the news and observer of raleigh nc and the detroit free press 
before he joined the new york times 
king joined the inquirer as a reporter in 1972 two years later 
he became city editor and left in 1976 for just over a year to 
write for forbes magazine he returned to the inquirer eventually 
becoming associate managing editor before moving to the business 
side of the operation in 1987 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

