<DOCNO> AP900801-0012 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the soviet union is piling up a record harvest 
but much of the grains and vegetables are expected to rot rather 
than ease the countrys worsening shortage of food 
the centrally planned economy has been unable to adjust to the 
bounty and the stunning yields reported by the news media are 
threatened by shortages of fuel storage space and transport 
while consumers face barren shelves in city grocery stores and 
officials warn of critical shortages by winter soviet television 
shows mounds of fresh wheat dumped in rural parking lots because 
grain elevators are full 
the soviet union annually loses 20 to 30 percent of its food 
harvest on the way to market grain and vegetables pour from leaky 
trucks rutted highways slow food convoys railroad schedules 
become scrambled and air transport for produce is rare 
last week russian federation president boris yeltsin ordered 
emergency incentives in his republic to prevent a catastrophe 
in the food supply other officials have warned of civil strife if 
the food shortages are not solved 
this is the moment when it is necessary to move from words to 
deeds or moscow could face winter without vegetables or 
potatoes food producers warned in a letter printed saturday on 
the front page of moskovskaya pravda 
it said much of the moscowarea vegetable crop was endangered by 
a shortage of hands for the harvest 
preliminary estimates indicate the grain crop in this critical 
year for soviet reform could top 230 million tons soviet 
television reported monday that would surpass last years record 
211 million tons and swamp 1988s mediocre tally of 195 million 
tons 
us experts predict the soviets will harvest 215 million tons 
of grain 
this year food grain harvests are enormous tass said 
reporting prime minister nikolai ryzhkovs visit to a farming area 
tuesday 
as one example tass said the saratov region is producing 44 to 
66 bushels per acre instead of the usual 66 to 88 bushels for the 
same range 
us wheat yields this year are running at 386 bushels per 
acre according to the department of agriculture 
ryzhkov also visited neighboring northern kazakhstan where one 
collective farm is producing three times as much grain as last 
year television news reported but 250 railcars a day are needed 
to haul it away and officials are able to provide only half that 
number 
farmers shown on soviet television suggested the radical step of 
allowing anyone to buy grain and store it themselves under soviet 
central planning collective farms grow grain and sell it to the 
state 
yeltsins emergency measures permit farmers in russia to sell on 
the open market 30 percent of the grain they are under contract to 
sell to the state at fixed prices according to the government 
newspaper izvestia 
yeltsin also promised that anyone who works on the harvest would 
be give special coupons allowing them to buy scarce consumer items 
soviet farms previously relied on temporary labor drafted from 
urban factories to help with the harvest but now that president 
mikhail s gorbachevs reforms call for factories to turn a profit 
they are refusing to send employees to the fields 
regional officials in yaroslavl declared a state of emergency 
and ordered local factories to provide labor to the farms izvestia 
reported 
in the southern republics of georgia and armenia a blockade of 
the railways has cut fuel deliveries to the farming areas that 
produce much of the soviet unions fresh fruits and vegetables 
tass news agency reported tuesday 
the blockade is aimed at enforcing promised multiparty reforms 
in georgia interfax said it has cut all train routes into georgia 
and armenia except those through azerbaijan armenia is locked in a 
deadly territorial dispute with azerbaijan 
meanwhile tass reported tuesday that yeltsin who is pushing 
his republic to more radical reforms than those approved by 
gorbachev has called a session of the russian congress for the end 
of october that session would consider the right to own land to 
inherit purchase and sell it tass reported tuesday 
gorbachev has called for longterm leasing of farmland but not 
outright ownership with the inherent right to earn a profit on 
buying and selling it which is abhorrent to diehard communists 
however gorbachev may be changing his views former politburo 
member yegor ligachev told reporters several weeks ago that he 
split with gorbachev because he could not agree with the soviet 
presidents new support for private property 
