<TEXT>
infants and toddlers would be required to sit 
in child safety seats on airline flights under legislation heading 
to the senate floor 
the measure approved tuesday by the commerce committee would 
order the federal aviation administration to require the seats on 
domestic airline flights it would be left to the faa to decide a 
height and weight limit for children needing the seats 
the committee approved the bill on a voice vote and sent it to 
the full senate no date has been scheduled for its consideration 
this is a great step forward for this bill we cannot continue 
to treat our youngest airline passengers like secondclass citizens 
when it comes to airline safety said sen christopher bond 
rmo who sponsored the legislation 
currently infants under 2 can fly free by traveling on the laps 
of a parent or guardian 
all of the major airlines permit infants to travel in safety 
seats which are attached to a regular airline seat and generally 
charge a reduced fare comparable to that for children between ages 
2 and 12 unticketed infants usually can use a vacant seat at no 
cost 
the airlines air transport association airline unions and 
consumer groups have advocated mandatory safety restraints 
generally for children under age 2 
the legislation stemmed from the death of a 23monthold child 
in a crashlanding of an airliner last year at sioux city iowa 
the accident killed 112 people three other children under age 2 
were injured 
a similar proposal by rep jim lightfoot riowa is pending in 
the house 
the national transportation safety board has recommended that 
approved safety seats be required for children under 40 inches in 
height or weighing less than 40 pounds 
the faa has said it would consider mandatory restraints but has 
proposed a regulation only to require that airlines allow child 
seats on board if passengers want to use them the practice 
already followed by the industry 
the faa in testimony before a house panel in midjuly said 
requiring child seats would end up costing more lives than it would 
save it estimated that the expense of buying tickets for infants 
would cause more families to travel by automobile and lead to 
increased numbers of traffic deaths and injuries 
the senate bill also calls for the united states to seek a 
similar child safety seat requirement for international flights 
from the international civil aviation organization 
