<TEXT>
the justice department is concerned that 
oliver norths victory before an appeals court could have a wider 
impact affecting other cases involving defendants who testify under 
a similar promise of immunity 
officials are reviewing the decision which held that the trial 
judge did not take proper steps to determine if norths 
congressional testimony influenced his trial said justice 
department spokesman dan eramian 
the department does not have a direct interest in the north case 
because the former white house aide was prosecuted by independent 
counsel lawrence e walsh 
in a 21 decision last month the us circuit court of appeals 
in washington ordered a witnessbywitness and review of the 
evidence presented at norths trial to determine if it was 
tainted by references to the testimony the former white house 
aide gave under a limited grant of immunity from prosecution 
that use immunity barred walsh from using any of norths 
testimony or information derived from it to prosecute the former 
marine lieutenant colonel 
eramian said justice department prosecutors were concerned about 
the cases impact in a limited number of cases in which a defendant 
is prosecuted after testifying before congress amidst widespread 
publicity 
justice department officials speaking on condition of 
anonymity said the decision could have more widespread 
applications as in case where courts or grand juries grant use 
immunity the procedural requirements set down by the court could 
be impossible for prosecutors to meet the officials said 
eramian stressed that the department was not necessarily 
considering participating in any appeal that walsh might undertake 
but if walsh appeals the decision the justice department could 
file a brief stating its legal position 
walsh has more than a month to decide whether to appeal the 
ruling to the full appellate court or ask the supreme court to 
review the issue 
norths weeklong appearance on capitol hill in 1987 received 
widespread television and newspaper coverage which his lawyers 
contend affected the memories of witnesses in the case 
the former national security council aide was placed on 
probation and ordered to perform 1500 hours of community service 
for his three felony convictions 
some legal experts say the decision by two appellate judges 
appointed by president reagan radically extended a 1972 supreme 
court decision that prohibits prosecutors from introducing a 
defendants compelled testimony as evidence 
what they did in this case was to virtually change use 
immunity into transactional immunity under which the government 
agrees not to prosecute someone in return for their cooperation 
said g robert blakey a notre dame law professor who drafted the 
1970 use immunity statute 
the court in effect created a rule that once anything was 
disseminated as widely as norths testimony it necessarily 
affected the trial blakey said there was nothing particularly 
unusual about the north testimony that it would irretrievably taint 
anybody who read it 
the two circuit judges who joined in the ruling laurence h 
silberman and david sentelle were both appointed by reagan and 
are generally regarded as members of the courts conservative wing 
patricia wald the appellate courts chief judge and the 
dissenter in the north case was appointed by president carter 
the two majority judges simply let north off blakey said 
if that sort of solicitude was paid to criminal defendants 
generally we wouldnt be talking about reagan judges 
</TEXT>
