<TEXT>
president bushs top economic adviser says no 
matter what additional clean air controls are approved by congress 
it will be expensive to the economy and result in job losses for 
some workers 
michael boskin chairman of the presidents council of economic 
advisers urged senate and house negotiators to hold down the cost 
of compromise clean air legislation and reiterated that bush 
opposes any bill that is substantially more expensive than the 20 
billion a year proposals he made last year 
the president is not prepared to see american firms workers 
and consumers overcharged or to see economic growth slowed 
needlessly boskin said in a letter to rep john dingell dmich 
dingell who heads the house negotiating team trying to work out 
a compromise clean air bill with the senate had asked for an 
economic assessment of the air pollution controls being considered 
on capitol hill 
house and senate staff members meanwhile met most of tuesday 
and were expected to continue discussions through the week as the 
two chambers work out differences in clean air bills approved 
earlier this year 
a compromise bill is unlikely to emerge from conference before 
late september 
in his letter to dingell boskin belittled suggestions that most 
of the additional costs to the economy of tougher air pollution 
controls could be offset by savings elsewhere instead he said 
the tighter controls will result in reduced productivity and hamper 
us industrys ability to compete with foreign industries 
environmentalists congressional supporters of tough new 
pollution controls as well as some senior officials of the 
environmental protection agency have argued that the substantial 
costs imposed on industry by the new clean air requirements would 
be offset by reduced health care spending and growth in new 
industries spawned by the need for pollution controls 
epa administrator william reilly has been among those who have 
argued that while some industries may suffer from the new 
requirements other businesses dealing in pollution control 
activities may prosper and provide new jobs as well as new exports 
the assertion that expanded clean air programs would on 
balance create jobs increase productivity and make the us 
economy more competitive in world markets are at best wishful 
thinking boskin wrote 
a spokesman for reilly said the epa chief agrees with boskins 
analysis reilly and boskin are eye to eye on this said epa 
spokesman dave cohen 
boskin said the administration proposal to congress would have 
added about 20 billion a year in new pollution control costs to 
the economy by the time all the new requirements go into effect in 
the year 2005 he said the bills approved by both the house and 
senate would cost 25 billion somewhat higher than previous 
administration estimates for the senate bill of 215 billion 
there was no explanation for the difference 
but boskin said if the most costly features of both the house 
and senate bills are kept in a final bill the cost could increase 
to 35 billion a year president bush has threatened to veto any 
clean air legislation he considers too costly or a threat to 
economic growth 
but boskin said that bush all along has known that tougher air 
pollution controls will be costly he is fully aware that any 
environmentally strong clean air bill will reduce real income 
growth and cause some temporary unemployment the president 
believes that our nation is able and should be willing to pay a 
reasonable price to clean its air 
</TEXT>
