<TEXT>
the house is completing work on a 
comprehensive housing bill that is under a veto threat because it 
disregards a presidential demand for higher down payments on 
mortgages backed by the federal housing administration 
the legislation expected to pass today must be reconciled with 
a different senate version that includes the tougher administration 
down payment requirements 
president bush threatened to veto any bill that would not keep 
the fha insurance fund solvent at a time of escalating defaults 
even before the house voted overwhelmingly tuesday night to 
require roughly the same cash down payments as under current law 
bush warned that such a requirement would be unacceptable 
the fha language was the main focus of debate tuesday night but 
it is only a portion of legislation that would authorize about 28 
billion for the governments housing and home ownership programs 
for fiscal 1991 
the comprehensive legislation would establish new programs to 
help firsttime home buyers permit lowincome americans receiving 
public housing assistance to own their homes and encourage 
production of new rental housing 
both the administration and house members agreed to an annual 
fee to be charged home buyers in order to keep the fha insurance 
fund solvent with the administrations proposed charge slightly 
smaller 
but the house plan adopted 4182 also requires the lower down 
payment requirements it was sponsored by reps bruce vento 
dminn and thomas ridge rpa 
the administration maintains that americans qualifying for fha 
mortgages should pay more up front than under current regulations 
because those who put up more cash will be less likely to default 
vento and ridge argued the administrations down payment 
requirements would make it impossible for thousands of americans to 
buy a home 
the fha payments at settlement would vary with the price of the 
house under the ventoridge language americans buying a 65000 
home would pay upfront charges of 4115 
the administration would require payments of 4939 on the same 
house 
the higher cost proposed by the administration would result from 
a requirement that buyers pay twothirds of the closing cost at 
settlement the ventoridge language would allow the closing costs 
to be financed through monthly mortgage payments 
the fha changes were a reaction to an analysis by the price 
waterhouse accounting firm which said the insurance fund is 
currently solvent but is losing money at an alarmingly fast rate 
the administration contends the savings and loan crisis has 
demonstrated the dangers of allowing an undercapitalized federal 
insurance program to operate on an unsound basis 
supporters of the ventoridge provision said the administration 
plan would exclude up to 100000 potential home buyers the 
administration has maintained that no more than 35000 people would 
be shut out 
voting against ventoridge were reps thomas petri rwis and 
jim cooper dtenn 
