<TEXT>
here at a glance are the major issues in 
campaign finance legislation before the senate 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
democrats want to set voluntary limits on how much senate 
candidates can spend in primary and general elections overall the 
ceilings would range from just under 2 million for a candidate 
from a small state to 103 million in california candidates could 
exceed the general election caps by 25 percent with contributions 
of 100 or less from instate voters 
republicans oppose absolute ceilings saying they inhibit the 
ability of challengers to raise enough money to overcome 
incumbents they offer flexible ceilings that would exempt 
money from instate donors and outofstate contributions of 250 
or less 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
democrats offer a variety of incentives to encourage candidates 
to abide by voluntary spending limits they would offer senate 
candidates a total of 20 million in government vouchers every 
twoyear election cycle to help pay for certain tv and radio ads 
republicans offer no public financing proposals 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
democrats would retain the current 1000 limit that an 
individual can contribute for each primary and general election 
the 25000 annual limit on what an individual can give to all 
candidates and party committees would be raised to 30000 
republicans would halve the 1000 ceiling on individual 
contributions from nonstate residents but they would exempt gifts 
to national and state party committees from the ceiling allowing 
individuals to give up to 340000 a year 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
both parties have agreed to a proposal by president bush to ban 
corporate union and trade association political action committees 
they doubt the ban could be extended to ideological pacs keyed to 
issues such as abortion or gun control because of constitutional 
questions 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
democrats would put new limits on spending by state party 
organizations for voter registration education and turnout 
activities 
republicans have no fixed ceiling on such spending but they 
would require state parties to subject a third of such expenses to 
federal limits on contributions 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
democrats would limit a candidates contributions to his own 
campaign to 250000 and bar candidates from repaying the money 
with contributions received after an election 
republicans would do the same they also would let the opponents 
of candidates who use more than 250000 of their own money raise 
contributions of up to 5000 from individuals up from 1000 
otherwiseequals 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
democrats would use public funds to subsidize threefourths of 
the cost of firstclass campaign mail up to a certain limit 
republicans would forbid members of congress from using their 
franking privilege for mass mailings during an election year 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
both parties would require broadcasters to make their best 
advertising slots available to candidates 45 days before a primary 
and 60 days before a general election at lowerthan standard rates 
</TEXT>
