<TEXT>
motorists in carcrazy southern california 
would have to leave their wheels at home every other day under 
proposals offered by the environmental protection agency for 
cleaning up the nations dirtiest air 
the plan offered tuesday is aimed at cutting ozone a major 
component of smog by 86 percent by early next century 
it is a backup to a cleanair plan approved in 1989 by the south 
coast air quality management district the epa plan would take 
effect only if state and regional governments in the districts 
area fail to reduce smog significantly 
the epa proposals were prompted by a lawsuit filed by 
environmentalists in 1982 
we have been very concerned that the local district has been 
backsliding said jan chattenbrown president of the coalition 
for clean air this plan will send a clear message if the 
district wont do the job the epa will step in 
the epa guidelines include a proposal for nodrive days if other 
methods fail to reduce ozone such a plan would use odd or even 
numbers on license plates to assign alternate driving days for the 
areas 12 million motorists 
it is in the spirit of presenting all possibilities that we 
are presenting the nodrive day it is not one we are 
endorsing said daniel w mcgovern epa western regional 
administrative director 
state and local authorities have been engaged in an 
extraordinary effort to address this problem themselves which we 
all hope will render a federal plan as unnecessary 
other features of the epa plan include reduction of emissions by 
6 percent a year from pollution sources such as household products 
industrial solvents and pesticides extending pollution control 
standards to construction equipment pleasure boats and offroad 
vehicles and a requirement that new motor vehicles are 85 percent 
to 90 percent cleaner than current vehicles 
the current threestep aqmd plan affects everything from lawn 
mowers to refineries at an estimated cost of 262 billion a year 
but later steps of that plan include the use of technology not 
yet developed making its effectiveness a guessing game 
in 1988 the most recent year available los angeles exceeded 
the national standard for ozone 150 times compared with 20 times 
for new york and chicago 
the federal plan takes longer to achieve goals set by the 
regional agency the aqmd plan calls for reducing current ozone 
averages by 86 percent in 2007 the epa by 2010 
