<TEXT>
in yet another move to end years of 
isolation as an orthodox communist state albania has announced its 
intention to permit joint ventures and other forms of foreign 
investment 
the presidium of the peoples assembly or parliament also 
approved a decree granting limited rights to stage public 
demonstrations and proposed setting up a special commission to 
consider constitutional changes 
the presidiums decisions were reported tuesday by the state 
news agency ata in a dispatch monitored in vienna it did not 
elaborate on the constitutional questions 
the moves come just weeks after about 5000 albanians flooded 
embassies in tirana the capital and received permission to leave 
their homeland 
many of the refugees complained of bleak economic prospects as 
well as the lack of political freedom albania is europes poorest 
country and last hardline communist state 
the new economic reforms apparently are designed to help 
alleviate the countrys economic backwardness and provide technical 
knowhow 
the decree on foreign investments stated that foreign 
embassies firms or individuals or albanians residing abroad can 
make investments or carry out related economic activities 
while the official announcement did not specifically mention 
joint ventures it said that enterprises with participation of 
foreign capital can carry out their economic activity in various 
sectors of the economy 
ata said the aim of such enterprises is the modernization of 
existing projects or the setting up of new projects with advanced 
technology 
it said joint ventures could help in extracting and processing 
raw materials increasing exports and decreasing dependence on 
imports producing more consumer goods and creating new jobs 
most contracts would require government approval ata said 
the presidiums decree on meetings gatherings and 
manifestations would grant albanians only limited freedom of 
assembly 
the decree as reported by ata apparently would continue to ban 
most antigovernment demonstrations including protests similar to 
those at embassies earlier this month 
such gatherings where appeals against the constitutional order 
are launched where calls are made for committing violations of 
the law where violations of relations with other countries are 
aimed at are banned the ata report said 
