pilot error and lack of routine guidance 
from air traffic controllers led to the 1988 crash of an indian 
airlines plane that killed all but two of the 135 people on board 
an inquiry published today said 
press trust of india quoted the report from the 
governmentappointed inquiry as saying there was no structural or 
mechanical failure involved in the crash of the 17yearold jet 
the boeing 737 on a flight from bombay to the western state of 
gujarat crashed in fog while approaching the airport 
the report which was submitted to the civil aviation ministry 
in january 1989 was published today in keeping with the 
governments decision to make public reports on air accidents the 
press agency said 
the inquiry report charged authorities at ahmedabad airport with 
failing to provide proper navigational aids and meteorological 
information to the aircraft 
at the time of the accident news reports said that approach 
lights at the airport were unserviceable and there was no proper 
firefighting services 
the report also attributed the crash to pilot error but did not 
give details the report did however say copilot deepak nagpal 
