<TEXT>
construction spending was flat in june after 
two consecutive monthly declines the government said today in a 
report pointing to further evidence of weakness in the building 
industry 
the commerce department reported that residential 
nonresidential and government construction spending totaled a 
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 4475 billion 
but it also said the declines in april and may were not as 
severe as first reported the april decline was revised from 22 
percent to 19 percent and the may drop was changed from 04 
percent to 03 percent spending had risen 04 percent in march 
despite the recent weakness construction spending in june was 
37 percent above that of the same month in 1989 when it totaled 
4316 billion 
spending in january and february posted large gains which 
analysts attributed to unseasonably warm weather that prompted some 
builders to steal activity scheduled for later in the year 
in addition high interest rates and tighter lending 
requirements have held back construction projects in some areas 
the industry weakness was suggested in the labor departments 
recent report showing a loss of 14000 construction jobs in june on 
top of a 179000 decline during the three previous months 
residential spending declined 22 percent to 1961 billion at 
an annual rate after falling an identical 22 percent the previous 
month 
singlefamily spending was off 35 percent to 1113 billion at 
an annual rate following a 40 percent decline in may 
apartment construction was unchanged at 308 billion after 
rising 15 percent the previous month 
nonresidential spending jumped 39 percent to 1071 billion 
after falling 09 percent in may leading the increase was a 102 
percent gain in spending on office buildings 
the oftenvolatile government sector edged down 01 percent to 
1084 billion after advancing 38 percent in may 
