<DOCNO> AP900801-0099 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the first press freedom law went into effect in 
the soviet union wednesday guaranteeing broad rights for 
journalists and potential publishers 
the law unanimously approved by the supreme soviet legislature 
in june after months of debate promises the press and other 
mass media are free and censorship of the mass media is 
forbidden 
censorship by the communist party the government and a special 
censorship agency kept the soviet news media under tight control 
before president mikhail s gorbachev came to power in 1985 
political pressure on the media began to lighten under 
gorbachevs policy of glasnost or openness but until now they 
still lacked legal protection from interference 
technically freedom of the press was guaranteed by a 
declaration in the soviet constitution but the new law is the 
first to spell out detailed guarantees of press freedoms 
soviet journalists new freedoms include the right to attend 
meetings and be present at the scene of disasters the right to 
refuse to prepare reports that are against a journalists 
convictions and the right to hold interviews with officials they 
now can withdraw their byline if the contents of a story are 
distorted by editing 
to establish a new publication or news organization the new law 
says soviets need only provide their name address frequency of 
publication circulation figures and source of financing 
all publications will be permitted except those calling for the 
violent overthrow of the government promoting racial or religious 
intolerance or publishing propaganda for war violence or cruelty 
but a bigger barrier is the shortage of newsprint and its 
increasing costs distribution of paper and printing plants will 
remain part of the state economy 
the law goes into effect at a time when there is an acute 
shortage of newsprint and printing services tass reported 
wednesday 
just when subscriptions are to be received the ussr 
ministry of communications announced the establishment of higher 
tariffs for the delivery of printing matter to subscribers as a 
result the price of most newspapers and magazines will at least 
double wiping out many publications 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

