<TEXT>
zhelyu zhelev who led the democratic 
opposition in junes free elections became president today the 
first noncommunist to gain any leading post in the balkan country 
in more than 40 years 
zhelevs election by parliament ended almost a month of 
political stalemate following the resignation july 6 of president 
petar mladenov a member of the ruling former communist party now 
known as the socialists 
mladenov stepped down after it was confirmed he had called for 
the use of tanks against antigovernment demonstrators last 
december 
zhelev 55 was a compromise candidate backed by all parties 
including socialist leaders after five unsuccessful attempts to 
get a president elected by the 400member parliament 
zhelev won 284 of the 389 votes cast today 
in a surprise move he immediately made a proposed former 
socialist interior minister atanas semerdzhiev as vice president 
deputies greeted the suggestion with applause and voted 
overwhelmingly for semerdzhiev in a show of hands only two 
deputies opposed the choice while seven abstained 
semerdzhiev had resigned as interior minister last week when a 
furor erupted over the proposed parliamentary appearance of todor 
zhivkov the stalinist leader ousted last fall after 35 years in 
power 
zhelev triumphed in the presidential race after none of the 
three original candidates proved able to secure the twothirds 
majority needed to win election in parliament 
although the socialists won junes free elections with 211 
parliamentary seats their incumbent premier andrei lukanov 
repeatedly has said he does not want to head a oneparty government 
spreading street protests against the socialists since the 
elections also have made clear that the ruling partys support is 
dwindling rapidly necessitating some sort of cooperation with the 
opposition union of democratic forces 
zhelev led the udf in the june elections in which the 16party 
coalition won 144 parliamentary seats 
before todays vote both zhelev and lukanov indicated that the 
socialists and opposition are willing to work together to ease 
bulgarias social tensions and rapidly deepening economic crisis 
answering questions from the floor zhelev said he wants to see 
bulgaria make a peaceful evolution to democracy with the direct 
participation of the political opposition 
while he did not directly retract previous opposition rejection 
of participation in a lukanovled coalition government he stressed 
the most important task of any president is now to work for the 
creation of a strong active and competent government 
observers in sofia took the remark as a sign the opposition is 
no longer excluding participation in government with the socialists 
for his part lukanov said his party had agreed to zhelevs 
candidacy as president in the interests of national welfare and 
noted this marked the effective end to oneparty monopoly of power 
in bulgaria 
the balkan nation was dominated by the communists since just 
after world war ii when the communists executed imprisoned and 
repressed their political opponents 
