<TEXT>
five european countries meeting for the 
first time as a new regional alliance agreed wednesday to step up 
political and economic cooperation to promote stability on the 
changing continent 
the leaders of italy czechoslovakia austria hungary and 
yugoslavia reached a wide range of accords aimed at strengthening 
democracy and spurring economic development in eastern and central 
europe 
the agreements came at the first summit of the socalled 
pentagonal initiative a regional alliance founded in budapest in 
november 1989 
all the delegations except italys were led by heads of 
government the host country was represented by deputy premier 
claudio martelli because premier giulio andreotti was forced to 
stay in rome to ensure passage of a bill in the chamber of deputies 
the leaders said the initiative should play a vital role in 
consolidating the political upheavals that have swept away 
communist regimes across eastern europe including in hungary and 
czechoslovakia 
shifting from ideological rivalry to the implementation of 
joint programs in the economic field and other sectors will be the 
most effective way of avoiding any temptation to revert to the 
past they said in a joint declaration 
the leaders said the new europe should be based on parliamentary 
and pluralistic democracy and a free market economy 
the choice is no longer the continuation of the classic game 
of balances but the construction of new forms of collaboration and 
integration martelli said in a speech in a period of such 
tumultuous change it is necessary to strengthen dialogue and 
reciprocal consultation 
officials said the alliance could help bring east european 
countries closer to the european community and act as a possible 
counterweight to the political and economic strength of a unified 
germany 
the bulk of the accords involved projects for improving 
transportation links between the countries the leaders agreed to 
establish four main road corridors and six railway lines and to 
expand air and maritime networks 
it is not yet known however where the funds for these projects 
will come among the observers at the summit were officials of the 
world bank and the european investment bank 
other agreements were reached in the fields of 
telecommunications the environment small and mediumsize 
enterprises scientific and technical research culture tourism 
and information 
a point of contention appeared to be the question of admitting 
poland to the group 
at a news conference hungarian premier jozsef antall said he 
supported the idea of including poland martelli however said no 
such request has been made and there were no immediate plans to 
expand the alliance 
austrian chancellor franz vranitsky said he proposed that the 
group study the possibility of abolishing nuclear power as his 
country has done 
this must be accepted by the majority he said it cant 
be implemented in a fortnight 
the leaders also took up the question of minorities a 
potentially explosive issue in several countries especially 
yugoslavia no specific decisions were made although hungary will 
chair a technical committee studying the problem 
