<TEXT>
the internal revenue service is losing its 
battle against overdue taxes which are growing faster than tax 
collections government auditors said wednesday 
each year irs falls farther and farther behind in its efforts 
to reduce the accountsreceivable balance paul l posner 
associate director of the general accounting office told the 
senate governmental affairs committee unless the problem is 
reduced he said it could have a serious negative impact on 
voluntary taxpayer compliance 
accounts receivable which the irs estimates grew from 30 
billion in 1984 to 66 billion last year represent taxes that 
have been assessed but not paid such as when a taxpayer files a 
return but fails to remit what is owed the irs says 13 million 
couples individuals and businesses are involved 
the irs the gao and other experts agree that accounts 
receivable may be exaggerated by as much as 50 percent accounts 
receivable are the total of unpaid income payroll and other taxes 
due over the last six years generally the legal maximum the irs 
can go back to in collecting taxes 
over the last six years posner said accounts receivable grew 
three times faster than collections of delinquent taxes and twice 
as fast as total net tax receipts he said it is especially 
disturbing that the average age of accounts is getting older 
meaning the debts are less likely to be collected 
this rapid outofcontrol growth in unpaid taxes threatens to 
overwhelm the irs and is absolutely unacceptable at a time when the 
administration and congress are grappling with painful revenue and 
spending choices said sen john glenn dohio chairman of the 
committee 
accounts receivable are different from the tax gap which is 
the difference in income taxes that are collected and what would be 
collected if individuals and businesses correctly reported their 
income and deductions the gap is expected to be about 100 billion 
this year alone 
irs commissioner fred t goldberg jr acknowledged that accounts 
receivable are a worrisome problem but said the agency is making 
progress 
for example he said the irs this year is collecting 472000 
in delinquencies for each staff member in the collections division 
up from 388000 two years ago the division is expected to collect 
265 billion this year compared with 233 billion in 1988 
goldberg said there has been a slow but steady increase in 
accounts the irs believes will never be collected because of death 
bankruptcy or inability to locate the debtor that 27 billion is 
in addition to the 66 billion 
goldberg said there will be dramatic reductions in accounts 
receivables only when irss 30yearold computer system is 
modernized when the agencys budget is stabilized so that staffer 
hiring and training can be improved and when tax laws are 
simplified 
president bushs budget for the irs for next year would allow 
hiring 1050 new collection personnel this represents the growth 
we can prudently manage and absorb during 1991 no more no less 
he said 
goldberg said that in february the irs had nearly 800000 
accounts totaling 18 billion that could not be worked because of 
lack of personnel that shortage was a result of a twoyear hiring 
freeze that was imposed on the irs he said 
john pepping an irs collections officer in the laguna niguel 
calif district said the personnel shortage there is so severe 
that as a rule no account under 50000 is sent to the field for 
collection he testified on behalf of the national treasury 
employees union which represents most irs workers 
robert m tobias president of the union urged congress to 
boost the irs budget sufficiently to hire 5000 new collectors over 
the next three years that would boost collections by 61 billion 
over five years he said 
