<TEXT>
efforts to develop drugs for aidsrelated 
diseases are hindered by federal rules which bar hospital insurance 
coverage for people receiving novel treatments the governments 
chief aids researcher said wednesday 
dr anthony s fauci and other witnesses told a house government 
operations subcommittee that the lack of public and private 
insurance for hospital care in clinical trials prevents thousands 
of people from receiving potentially lifeprolonging treatment 
insurers including the public medicare and medicaid programs 
do not regularly reimburse for treatments that are considered to be 
experimental a person with an aidsrelated infection who does not 
receive experimental treatment would be reimbursed according to 
fauci and others 
both aids research and the healthcare reimbursement programs 
fall under the jurisdiction of the department of health and human 
services 
aids and the particularly virulent opportunistic infections 
that follow it strike largely at people least able to afford 
hospital care witnesses said 
the infections strike all organs including the eyes lungs and 
intestines and along with tumors cause most aids deaths aids 
weakens the bodys ability to resist ordinary bacteria fungi 
parasites and viruses 
fauci told the subcommittee on human resources and 
intergovernmental relations that he has brought up the gap in 
biweekly meetings of the interagency hiv leadership group 
the response within the department is that they were very 
sympathetic with the difficulties this is posing for us in the 
conduct of our trials but a solution is not readily at hand 
fauci said 
he said the problem is an unwillingness to spend more money on 
reimbursements that are already stretching the government for 
nonexperimental hospitalizations 
we do not agree from the biomedical research and health care 
delivery standpoint with that philosophy said fauci director of 
the national institute of allergy and infectious diseases at the 
national institutes of health 
hospitalization is required for aids patients with opportunistic 
infections because the infection is usually acute and patients must 
be monitored around the clock said dr fred r sattler of the 
university of southern californias school of medicine 
the hearing was called to examine the status of research into 
drugs used to prevent or treat opportunistic infections and the 
priority given by the nih to research into those drugs rather than 
an overall cure for aids 
