senators warned the state departments 
designated legal adviser wednesday about a looming confrontation 
with the bush administration over the parliamentary form of the 
recent ussoviet agreement banning chemical weapons 
president bush and soviet leader mikhail gorbachev signed the 
accord at their summit in june the measure calls for the two 
countries to destroy most of existing stockpiles and end the 
production of new weapons 
at issue is whether the proposal should be an executive 
agreement which the bush administration wants or a treaty which 
the senate wants 
a treaty must be ratified by the president with the approval of 
twothirds of the senate an executive agreement such as the one on 
chemical weapons requires a majority vote in the house and senate 
sen joseph biden dny said 18 of the 19 members of the 
senate foreign relations committee think it should be a treaty 
he told edwin d williamson who has been nominated as the 
departments legal adviser that at a minimum i would hope to 
elicit the constitutional basis for the administrations current 
view that this accord should be an executive agreement not a 
treaty 
williamson said he needed to study the issue further because his 
initial impression was that the measure should be a treaty 
if approved by the senate williamson will succeed abraham 
sofaer a south carolina native williamson 50 has spent most of 
