<TEXT>
lawmakers on wednesday elected democratic 
opposition leader zhelyu zhelev as bulgarias first noncommunist 
president in more than four decades thousands poured into the 
streets in a spontaneous celebration 
the election of zhelev a 55yearold philosopher turned 
politician ended a nearly 4weekold political standoff after the 
july 6 resignation of president petar mladenov a member of the 
ruling communist party now known as the socialists 
mladenov had been popular for steering bulgaria toward junes 
free elections but resigned after it was proved he had urged the 
use of tanks in december against antigovernment demonstrators 
thousands of supporters of zhelevs opposition alliance the 
union of democratic forces celebrated in the streets of sofia a 
udf stronghold they chanted victory udf and zhelyu 
it is a great day today said one supporter nadia 
mihailova 55 the balance of power has been achieved and 
hopefully things will quiet down 
zhelev who led the udf in the june elections that the 
socialists won became president after the 400seat legislature 
failed in five previous attempts to elect a new head of state he 
is the first noncommunist to gain any leading post in the balkan 
nation in more than 40 years 
zhelev was a compromise candidate backed by all parties 
including socialist leaders and won 284 of the 389 votes cast he 
ran uncontested after all parties withdrew their initial candidates 
incumbent socialist premier andrei lukanov told the house before 
the vote that zhelevs election would mean a final rejection of 
the factual monopoly over power 
his remarks indicated a commitment to pluralism in the socialist 
party the only former communist party in eastern europe to win 
free elections the socialists won 211 seats in the june elections 
while the udf took 144 
lukanov had repeatedly said that despite his partys victory in 
the june elections he did not want to lead a oneparty government 
spreading street protests against the socialists have also made 
clear that the ruling partys support is dwindling rapidly 
necessitating some sort of cooperation with the opposition 
students and intellectuals have staged protests and strikes 
since the june elections to demand democratic reforms 
before wednesdays vote both zheev and lukanov indicated that 
the socialists and opposition were willing to work together to ease 
bulgarias social tensions and rapidly deepening economic crisis 
in his comments before the vote zhelev said he wanted to see 
bulgaria make a peaceful evolution to democracy with the direct 
participation of the political opposition 
immediately following his victory zhelev made a surprise move 
and proposed former socialist interior minister atanas semerdzhiev 
as vice president 
deputies greeted the suggestion with applause and voted 
overwhelmingly for semerdzhiev in a show of hands only two 
deputies opposed the choice and seven abstained 
semerdzhiev resigned as interior minister last friday when a 
furor erupted over the proposed appearance in parliament of todor 
zhivkov the stalinist leader ousted last fall after 35 years in 
power 
the appointment of semerdzhiev was seen as a move to narrow the 
widening rift between the socialists and the opposition 
