<TEXT>
got a hankering for some exxon valdez 
halibut a craving for beach crew chili 
if baked alaska sounds oldfashioned perhaps alaska crude 
chocolate cake will satisfy 
these and other culinary concoctions were submitted by exxon 
corp workers elected officials and others involved in the cleanup 
of the nations biggest oil spill the recipes are collected in 
the two billion dollar cookbook 
the title refers to the amount exxon reported spending to clean 
up nearly 11 million gallons of crude spilled from the exxon valdez 
in march 1989 
a few fanciful names aside there is little in the cookbook to 
remind readers it was an oil spill that brought the contributors of 
the recipes to prince william sound 
we wanted to show some of the good story and the good news of 
whats happened with all of those people that got together to work 
on the cleanup said kay harrington one of four women who put 
together the cookbook while their exxonemployed husbands worked on 
the spill 
the oil spill was the proverbial lemon and this was an effort 
to make some lemonade 
according to its foreword the cookbook aims to celebrate the 
richness of friendships and the priceless feeling of accomplishment 
of a job well done 
but perhaps more importantly it adds our hope is that 
you will find our book a recipe for healing 
healing and humor are welcome in the aftermath of the spill 
said alaska environmental commissioner dennis kelso who hadnt 
seen the cookbook 
he cautioned against treating the cleanup as if it were over and 
done with or forgetting the damage the spill did 
the cookbook financed by 31 corporations and individuals 
including exxon went on the shelves of stores in alaska and 
houston last week exxon also has the book on sale at its anchorage 
offices 
the books pages are sprinkled with upbeat bits of information 
it includes photos of a clean prince william sound there are 
anecdotes about people who met married or had babies while working 
on the spill 
first lady barbara bush sent a recipe for allamerican clam 
chowder gov steve cowper added one for buttermilk pie sen ted 
stevens ralaska contributed one for salmonburgers 
exxon valdez halibut a mix of halibut mayonnaise mustard and 
seasoning invented in an exxon trailer in valdez was submitted 
by mona cadoret of lafayette la 
texas and cajun cuisine are well represented reflecting exxons 
houston roots 
the last recipe in the book is for soap 
