<TEXT>
the owners of the crippled three mile island 
nuclear reactor will seek to have customers pay costs associated 
with the 1979 accident until the year 2014 according to plant 
officials 
the unit operated only about four months before it was 
permanently disabled in the nations worst commercial nuclear 
accident on march 31 1979 its twin unit 1 was unharmed and was 
given permission to resume operations in 1985 the owners hope to 
operate the healthy unit until 2014 
its wrong to ask our children to pay for a nuclear reactor 
that only was in operation for four months eric epstein 
spokesman for three mile island alert an antinuclear group said 
in an interview wednesday 
the costs are the result of the reactors unique 
postaccident condition plant officials said in a july 26 report 
filed with the nuclear regulatory commission 
because of the accident the report says it will cost 1956 
million to safely get rid of the damaged unit about 70 million 
more than for a comparable reactor that did not suffer an accident 
the plants pennsylvania owners intend to ask state utility 
regulators to permit them to start billing customers for the full 
amount when they make their next rate filings probably in 1992 or 
1993 said mary wells a spokeswoman for general public utilities 
nuclear the plant operator 
it is standard practice for utilities to ask ratepayers to fund 
decommissioning the formal term for mothballing or dismantling a 
plant at the end of its energyproducing life 
but three mile island poses a more difficult question 
pennsylvania consumer advocate irwin popowsky said in an interview 
wednesday 
we have not opposed reasonable decommissioning costs for other 
units on the theory that ratepayers who receive service ought to be 
accumulating money to decommission it later popowski said 
but tmi2 is unique because it only provided service for a 
short time its certainly going to be an issue he said 
rates for the 426000 customers of metropolitan edison co 
which owns 50 percent of the plant could increase as much as 4 
percent plant officials said last month meanwhile rates for 
customers of pennsylvania electric co and jersey central power amp 
light co which each own 25 percent of both units could see rates 
rise 1 percent to 2 percent the officials said 
in the accident unit 2 was allowed to lose vital cooling water 
that normally covers the nuclear fuel rods 
financed partly by ratepayers the subsequent 1 billion cleanup 
has focused on removal of fuel from the damaged radioactive core 
waste shipment and water decontamination 
plant officials hope to finish the cleanup by the end of 1991 
then place unit 2 in storage for anywhere between 20 years and 60 
years while radiation decays inside the decommissioning money 
would then be recalled and the plant could either be dismantled or 
sealed 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

