<TEXT>
zhelyu zhelev the new bulgarian 
president was a man of letters rather than politics before last 
years politburo coup that toppled the hardline communist 
leadership 
as in other east european countries abandoning stalinism 
bulgarias parliament on wednesday chose for the presidency an 
intellectual untainted by a communist past 
zhelev an opposition leader was the first noncommunist to 
gain a top post in bulgaria where the former communists now 
called socialists still hold an absolute majority in the grand 
national assembly 
but his election to the highest office illustrated the swift and 
unrelenting decline of the socialists who now admit that despite 
their june election victory they are not strong enough to govern 
alone 
zhelev practically unknown in bulgaria just over a year ago 
gained prominence as chairman of the union of democratic forces 
the main opposition alliance comprising 16 diverse political 
parties 
he was the only candidate in wednesdays presidential balloting 
the ruling socialists the mainstream agrarians and the union had 
withdrawn their candidates in an effort to break a deadlock in 
parliament 
last spring zhelev led the opposition in talks with the former 
communists that forced the ruling party to move toward a multiparty 
system and bulgarias first free elections in 58 years 
while lacking charisma and political experience at the outset 
zhelev became a respected leader and gained considerable popularity 
in sofia and other urban centers mainly among intellectuals and 
the countrys youth 
it was the slightly built zhelev who stepped into an angry crowd 
of students and other protesters who had blocked traffic in 
downtown sofia to demonstrate against alleged manipulations in the 
june parliamentary elections 
days earlier on june 7 zhelev was the main speaker at a rally 
of 500000 union supporters in downtown sofia the biggest such 
event ever in modern bulgarian times 
before last years changes zhelev was known only to a small 
group of intellectuals who managed to get a copy of his book 
fascism published in 1981 a searching analysis of 
totalitarianism the book was soon banned and has become a 
bestseller only with its republication this year 
in other east european nations democratic changes that began 
last fall are also being led by dissident intellectuals 
in czechoslovakia vaclav havel rose to the presidency as a 
dissident playwright who had been jailed and harassed for years 
his ideas and plays had won acclaim abroad but were banned at home 
similarly hungarys interim president arpad goencz spent 
seven years in jail after the 1956 revolution and then was active 
as a writer and translater of english and french literature 
born march 3 1935 zhelev studied philosophy at sofia 
university from 195861 he worked in the house of culture in 
veselinovo near shumen in northern bulgaria 
in 196164 he engaged in postgraduate studies but failed to 
complete them with a dissertation because he had criticized lenins 
theory of matter he was expelled from the communist party in 1964 
for the next eight years zhelev was either jobless or worked in 
casual jobs in agriculture in his wifes hometown 
starting in 1972 he worked for two years as a sociologist and 
joined the institute of culture in sofia in 1975 where he has been 
active since except for a period when he was expelled 
also in 1975 zhelevs thesis was finally accepted and he 
graduated as a doctor of philosophy 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

