<TEXT>
the senate told its public esteem is at the 
level of usedcar salesmen voted 7723 on wednesday to bar its 
members from accepting fees for speeches to specialinterest 
groups but immediate skepticism was raised as to whether the 
decision will hold 
the vote approved an amendment by sen christopher dodd 
dconn to a campaign finance overhaul bill it requires senators 
to quit giving speeches for profit as of next jan 1 
but later action by the senate and a renewed veto threat by the 
bush administration regarding the overall bill raised doubts that 
the honoraria ban will make its way into the books anytime soon 
this bill clearly will not become law said sen mitch 
mcconnell rky he said white house chief of staff john sununu had 
told him earlier wednesday that bush would veto it 
the measures chances also were complicated as the senate began 
piling other amendments onto it some of them likely to virtually 
eliminate any chance of twothirds vetoproof support for the 
package 
for example the senate barely approved 5149 new york sen 
daniel moynihans proposal requiring members to forgo unearned 
income of more than 15 percent of their regular salaries that 
would be a hard blow to the senates many millionaires whose stock 
and interest incomes far exceed their government paychecks 
sen lloyd bentsen dtexas one of those millionaires said 
it looks like a little bit of class warfare going on he said 
he wouldnt stay in the senate if the moynihan provision became law 
also approved was on a 5941 vote was an amendment by sen pete 
wilson rcalif that would prohibit senate candidates from 
tapping earmarked funds to help pay for television ads until 
congress first sets aside 100 million for drug prevention centers 
i dont know whether this bill is going anywhere said 
senate republican leader bob dole of kansas unless theres some 
changes thats not going to be possible 
senators can now pocket up to 27337 in outside speaking fees 
to supplement their annual salary of 98400 
when a significant part of our salaries comes from hustling 
and thats what it amounts to we denigrate ourselves said dodd 
as public servants our salaries should come from the public 
alone 
sen robert c byrd dwva said members of the senate 
himself among them had supplemented their salaries with more than 
9 million in honoraria over the past decade 
the scandals of the past two years have put a black mark on 
public service and raised public cynicism to an alltime high 
byrd said were about at the level of used car salesmen in the 
publics esteem 
the senate voted last week to denounce sen david durenberger 
rminn for violating several ethics standards including skirting 
the limits on honoraria in a bookpublishing deal 
six other senators are under investigation by the senate ethics 
committee for alleged actions involving savings and loan 
institutions and department of housing and urban development 
programs 
the house voted last year to give up honoraria effective jan 1 
1991 but also boosted the salaries of its members to 124000 
reluctant to vote itself the same 25 percent pay boost the senate 
instead retained the opportunity for its members to accept 
specialinterest fees 
republicans who particularly oppose the campaign bills 
provisions for aggregate spending ceilings and government vouchers 
for buying tv advertising have lost several partyline votes in 
their attempts to amend it 
dodd who reported 15000 in honoraria income in 1989 called 
the vote on his amendment significant regardless of bushs veto 
threat saying it puts the senate on record for the first time in 
favor of abolishing honoraria he said he will add it to other 
legislation if the campaign finance bill falters 
in 1989 senators accepted nearly 3 million in honoraria and 
kept more than 21 million with the balance donated to charity 
according to their financial disclosure forms 
dole who kept 35750 in honoraria in 1989 said he agreed with 
dodd on the need to eliminate such income but not on the strategy 
of doing it without a pay raise 
in january house members will be getting paid about 22000 
more than senators and we could be getting about 22000 less 
for years to come he said 
dole said he had considered trying to amend dodds measure to 
include a raise that would return senate and house salaries to 
parity but acknowledged he lacked the votes to win its passage 
this close to the november election 
dodds amendment also would limit senate members earned outside 
income to 15 percent of their salaries a policy that the house 
also adopted a year ago 
