<TEXT>
a defendant in the socalled central park jogger 
trial testified wednesday he never admitted to police that he took 
part in a gangrape and nearfatal beating 
testifying for the second day yusef salaam 16 admitted he was 
in the park april 19 1989 the night the female jogger was nearly 
killed but he said he never saw her 
his testimony contradicted that of detective thomas mckenna 
mckenna last week said he tricked salaam into admitting he had 
attacked the jogger and others in the park mckenna said he made 
notes of those admissions 
salaam also denied that he saw his two codefendants antron 
mccray 16 and raymond santana 15 in the park that night and 
denied he told mckenna most of the things in his notes 
salaam said he did tell mckenna that on the day after the 
rampage through the park others told him people had been attacked 
there the night before 
salaam mccray and santana are on trial on charges of attempted 
murder rape sexual abuse assault robbery and riot for allegedly 
attacking the woman and two male joggers mccray and santana 
admitted taking part in the attack in videotape statements shown to 
the jury there is no videotape of salaam 
the defendants are being tried in an adult court but if 
convicted they will be sentenced as juvenile offenders to up to 10 
years in prison 
the jogger nearly dead when found and suffering brain injuries 
underwent rehabilitation and has returned to salomon brothers inc 
where she is a vice president in corporate finance she still has 
difficulty walking and does not remember the attack 
three other youths steven lopez and kevin richardson both 15 
and kharey wise 17 are to stand trial on the same charges later 
this year 
on tuesday salaam testified that he told detectives that he was 
15 almost immediately when they came to his home to pick him up it 
is illegal for police to question anyone under 16 without a parent 
present 
defense attorney robert burns says police knowingly questioned 
salaam illegally and therefore any alleged incriminating statements 
by him should be discounted 
on crossexamination assistant district attorney elizabeth 
lederer suggested salaam was lying when he said he told police he 
was 15 
she suggested he knew he could be questioned alone if police 
thought he was 16 and that he thought he could submit to 
interrogation and return home without his mother finding out 
he admitted he knew other teenagers had been questioned by 
police about the previous nights events and released but he 
denied telling police he was 16 and hoping to be questioned without 
his mother knowing 
