a stockbroker who killed a client he 
had defrauded and then fabricated clues to throw off police has 
been sentenced to 40 years in prison 
frank a vandever 36 fatally shot ronald w hiiri in his 
stonington home in 1988 then created phony clues suggesting the 
killing was connected to drugs and sex 
vandever who pleaded guilty may 25 murdered hiiri to prevent 
him from reporting that vandever had embezzled money from him the 
prosecution said 
i am really and sincerely sorry your honor vandever said 
tuesday before being sentenced by superior court judge joseph 
koletsky 
four days before the slaying vandever was fired from a new 
haven brokerage firm after company officials discovered he had 
taken 43000 from a womans account and deposited it in his own 
savings account prosecutors said 
vandever had promised to make restitution and assured company 
officials he had not embezzled money from any other clients he 
decided to kill hiiri because he was worried hiiri would report 
that he too was missing money said assistant states attorney 
kevin t kane 
he said vandever once told a traveling companion he was writing 
a book on the perfect murder 
in some ways this murder could have been perfect kane said 
after shooting hiiri first in the back and then at pointblank 
range in the heart vandever left newspapers and books around 
hiiris house to make police believe he was a transvestite or 
homosexual hiiris wallet showed up in an area of bridgeport known 
for drug trafficking 
despite vandevers efforts he was immediately a suspect 
hiiris family knew he was to meet with his stockbroker the day he 
was killed and vandever was videotaped by a suspicious jeweler 
while trying to buy a ring with hiiris credit card 
