<TEXT>
president fw de klerk on 
wednesday accused nelson mandelas african national congress of a 
breach of trust that has jeopardized blackwhite talks on 
ending apartheid 
de klerk met mandela for three hours in pretoria and then issued 
a strongly worded statement criticizing the anc and its close ally 
the south african communist party 
a dispute over official assertions that militants in both groups 
are planning for an insurrection has eroded good will developed in 
recent months between the government and the anc mandelas group 
is the leading black opposition movement 
earlier wednesday mandela issued a conciliatory statement after 
the talks with de klerk but de klerks remarks showed that deep 
divisions persist over the alliance between the anc and the 
communists 
statements and actions by prominent anc members as well as by 
communist party members seriously jeopardize the continuation 
of discussions aimed at the creation of a climate for 
negotiation de klerk said in his statement wednesday 
the president said his meeting with mandela took place in a 
constructive spirit he said aug 6 talks between the 
government and the anc on ending whiteminority rule would proceed 
as planned 
however in accusing the anc and communists of a breach of 
trust he apparently referred to the recent police allegations 
that militants from those organizations have been plotting to seize 
power by force if negotiations break down 
de klerk said law and order minister adriaan vlok would issue 
statements about important information obtained by police and 
the recent arrests of dozens of anc and communist party members 
in his earlier remarks wednesday mandela had said i am 
positive that the talks on the 6th of august will go ahead in good 
spirit 
mandela said he told de klerk that the anc and the communist 
party were committed to peaceful negotiations not violent 
revolution 
he also indicated the two men had cleared up a 
misunderstanding about the presence of communist party leader 
joe slovo on the anc negotiating team 
after a de klerkmandela meeting last week the anc said the 
government wanted slovo dropped from the anc delegation 
i thought that the state president had demanded that joe slovo 
be excluded from the delegation of the anc mandela said 
the correct position is that the state president was disturbed 
by evidence placed before him mandela said in a reference to the 
police allegations 
the statement gave no indication that slovo would be dropped 
from the negotiating team 
slovo is one of several communists who also hold top posts in 
the anc mandela is not a member of the communist party and says 
the anc is not a communist organization despite the 
crossmembership 
mandela and slovo appeared together at a communist party rally 
on sunday and again denied the existence of a plot to seize power 
however anc leaders have said that guerrillas will continue to 
infiltrate the country until a ceasefire is negotiated with the 
government 
the anc and the government held their first talks in may three 
months after de klerk legalized the group and freed mandela from a 
life prison term for plotting against the government mandela 
deputy president of the anc had spent 27 years in prison 
the talks aug 6 will be aimed at eliminating obstacles to 
fullscale negotiations on a new constitution to give the black 
majority a voice in national affairs 
before the anc enters negotiations it wants the government to 
release prisoners convicted of political crimes and allow the 
return without punishment of about 20000 south african exiles 
under apartheid the 5 million whites dominate politics and the 
economy and the 30million black majority has no voice in national 
affairs 
the ancs guerrilla campaign launched in 1961 has never posed 
a serious threat to the governments powerful security forces the 
anc has not carried out any major attacks in recent months 
