<TEXT>
the house foreign affairs committee approved 
on wednesday new restrictions on trade with iraq as democrats on 
the panel chastised president bush for not taking such action on 
his own 
the legislation approved on a voice vote without dissent calls 
for an end to the 200 million line of credit iraq now enjoys 
through the exportimport bank and for us opposition to loans 
from international institutions like the world bank 
it also would require that any us exporter wishing to sell 
items to iraq first prove that they will not be used for any 
program to develop chemical or biological weapons or ballistic 
missiles or enhance iraqs ability to support terrorism 
the bills author rep howard berman dcalif said the united 
states must register its disapproval of human rights violations by 
iraq and the belligerent rhetoric of its president saddam hussein 
iraq has massed 100000 troops on its border with kuwait in a 
dispute over oil production 
the lesson of iraq is clear berman said you win nothing 
by appeasing a bully he merely becomes a bolder and more dangerous 
bully 
a day earlier assistant secretary of state john kelly testified 
before a house subcommittee that the administration is developing 
new curbs on socalled dual use exports goods like computers 
and aircraft parts that can have either a civilian or military 
purpose 
but berman said his legislation goes farther because it puts the 
burden on exporters to show that their products will not be used in 
weapons programs 
i regret that the administration has long been unwilling to 
take a stance and consider sanctions berman said 
and rep william broomfield of michigan the panels senior 
republican said he hoped the committee action would spur the 
administration to complete its review of policy toward iraq and 
recommend a policy we all can support 
the action came after the nearsale to iraq last month of 
industrial furnaces that could be used to make nuclear weapons 
material the sale was aborted by the white house at the last 
minute 
documents obtained by the associated press show that officials 
at the commerce department who had previously approved the sale 
knew that the furnaces had a potential nuclear use 
the documents are the minutes of the departments discussions in 
1989 with consarc corp the rancocas njbased furnace 
manufacturer 
they show that officials of the company that made the furnaces 
consarc corp of rancocas nj held a meeting on feb 22 1989 
with alan c stoddart a special agent from commerces office of 
export enforcement 
mr stoddart said the departments main concern is nuclear 
nonproliferation according to the minutes of the meeting with 
consarcs president raymond roberts and tina olnick a company 
employee 
the minutes continued mr roberts again stated that the 
customer tells us they will be making titanium castings for making 
medical prostheses 
however the equipment can be used without modification on 
zirconium for which the principal end use is nuclear 
in an earlier feb 15 1989 conversation roberts told jeff 
tripp of the commerce department that there is nothing to stop 
them the iraqis from melting zirconium the main use of which is 
cladding material for nuclear fuel 
gary milhollin executive director of the wisconsin project on 
nuclear arms control said the highperformance furnaces such as 
the ones iraq sought can be used for a number of purposes 
including melting plutonium for bomb cores and titanium for missile 
nose cones 
the iraqis said the titanium a lightweight metal would be used 
for artificial hip and knee joints for victims of the persian gulf 
war with iran 
on march 15 1989 ms olnick consarcs contract administrator 
asked the commerce department whether the company needed a 
validated export license to ship the furnaces 
such a license is generally needed to export items that would 
appear to have a direct nuclear capability 
in the letter ms olnick said consarc did not believe a 
validated license was necessary but we would appreciate an 
assessment of the department of commerce 
she added we have informed the customer that we will not 
proceed with the project until we have received approval to export 
the equipment in either the form of an assessment that an export 
license is not required or an approved export license 
roberts did not return a telephone call wednesday to discuss the 
documents but he said earlier his company had received permission 
to ship furnaces to iraq ms olnick said she could not talk about 
the matter 
commerce department officials have refused to talk about the 
consarc case 
but after a furnace was seized by the customs service on a dock 
in philadelphia last month us officials said consarc would be 
required to obtain a validated license it is unlikely such a 
license will be granted they said 
