chairman john e frohnmayer of the national 
endowment for the arts says he might appoint local panels to help 
determine whether federally financed works of art violate community 
antiobscenity standards 
frohnmayer said the need for such a move had never arisen 
because an nea grant had never been denied or challenged under the 
congressional ban on federal support for works that might be 
considered obscene 
if we were required to at some point determine local 
standards thats how we would go about it or that is one of the 
ways one might go about it he said 
the nea chairman expressed his views during a threehour 
deposition taken tuesday by new york lawyer floyd abrams who is 
representing the new school for social research in a lawsuit 
against the endowment a transcript of the 100page deposition was 
released wednesday 
the new school is challenging the endowments requirement that 
grant recipients sign a pledge they will not use federal funds to 
create obscene art the lawsuit charges that the pledge is 
unconstitutionally vague and violates guarantees of free speech and 
due process 
the new schools application for a 45000 grant to redesign its 
main courtyard in new york was approved by the endowment last march 
but when informed of the neas antiobscenity restrictions new 
school president jonathan f fanton wrote frohnmayer that the 
university could not accept the endowment grant under a condition 
that undermines our societys deep commitment to intellectual and 
artistic freedom 
frohnmayer responded in a may 2 letter to fanton which expressed 
severe questions about the constitutionality of the law 
frohnmayers deposition will be used by abrams a noted first 
amendment lawyer when the case is heard before us district judge 
louis stanton in manhattan on aug 13 
the nea chairmans proposal to appoint local panels to judge 
whether endowmentsupported works might be obscene follows a 
formula prescribed by the supreme court in its landmark 1973 
obscenity ruling 
the high court said determinations of obscenity must take into 
account contemporary community standards the court said works 
may be considered obscene if they depict sex in a patently 
offensive way appeal to the prurient interest and lack serious 
literary artistic political or scientific value 
under questioning by abrams frohnmayer said he might find it 
necessary to consider impaneling a group within a locality in 
which that grant was going to take place to advise the endowment on 
community standards 
but so far he said we have not been confronted with that 
issue because there has been no grant that has been denied or 
challenged under this statute 
he denied that the endowment had rejected any grant application 
on the grounds that it was considered too controversial or 
troublesome since the antiobscenity ban was imposed by congress 
last october 
the nea was plunged into controversy more than a year ago when 
sen jesse helms rnc and other political and religious 
conservatives criticized endowment support for exhibitions of 
controversial works by photographer robert mapplethorpe and artist 
andres serrano 
at helms urging congress amended the endowments current 171 
million budget to include a ban on using federal funds for artworks 
that include depictions of sadomasochism homoeroticism the 
sexual exploitation of children or individuals engaged in sex acts 
and which when taken as a whole do not have serious literary 
artistic political or scientific works 
