the federal communications commission on 
wednesday proposed to make it easier for handicapped people to gain 
advanced amateur radio licenses 
the commission by a 50 vote proposed that examiners be able 
to exempt mentally or physically impaired individuals who have 
extraordinary difficulty in passing highspeed morse code 
telegraphy proficiency tests 
currently amateur licensees must pass a written exam and 
demonstrate proficiency of five words per minute in morse code in 
order to gain a novice or technicians license 13 wpm for the 
general or advanced classes and 20 wpm for the amateur extra class 
the fcc proposed that applicants for higher classes could be 
exempted from the 13 wpm or 20 wpm exams if they have a doctors 
certificate stating they cannot pass the telegraphy exams and if 
they hold a current or renewable novice technician general or 
advanced class operators license 
international radio rules require a proficiency of 5 wpm or more 
in other 50 votes wednesday the fcc 
proposed establishing standards for conducting comparative 
renewal proceedings between cellular radio licensees and license 
challengers when existing lotteryawarded licenses begin to expire 
in 1993 the commission proposed weighting the process in favor of 
incumbents in the booming 3 billion cellular business 
opened an inquiry into setting standards for the possible 
introduction of digital audio radio services which would provide a 
compact disc quality sound better than todays am and fm 
broadcasts three applications are pending for such service 
extended its inquiry into possible changes in rules governing 
socalled television satellite stations which rebroadcast to small 
communities all or most of the programming of a parent station 
