latest documents called statements of contested facts in his 
sevenpage paper bush contends that before he joined the silverado 
board he disclosed his relationships with good and walters to 
former silverado chairman michael wise other silverado managers 
the board of directors and the thrifts attorneys 
good and walters invested millions of dollars in bushs oil 
partnership jnb exploration co which drilled a number of dry 
holes in wyoming over two years and failed to become profitable as 
a director bush voted to approve some loans by silverado to good 
and walters but did not vote on others 
bush also asserts in his document that he made no agreement to 
abstain from votes involving loans to good or walters 
in its ninepage submission the ots says there is no 
evidence that a letter prepared by wise about bushs business 
dealings with the two men was actually sent the letter was 
addressed to silverados preferred shareholders and was accompanied 
by a cover memo to the directors the ots notes 
the document alleges that bush breached his duty to silverado 
shareholders when he voted to approve certain loans to good and 
walters five of those loans resulted in a combined loss to 
silverado of at least 46 million the ots says 
generally accepted standards of prudent operation require the 
disclosure of a thrift directors relationships with major 
customers of the institution when further transactions are under 
consideration the agencys document says 
