<TEXT>
a un conference to promote 
breastfeeding denounced on wednesday the practice of distributing 
baby formula free to new mothers particularly those in developing 
nations 
the conference urged closer regulation of the marketing of baby 
formula to encourage breastfeeding which is considered a key to 
lowering infant mortality doctors said even mothers who have 
tested positive for the aids virus should breastfeed 
attainment of the goal demands vigorously defending 
against a bottlefeeding culture said a declaration on the third 
and final day of the conference the conference was led by the 
world health organization and unicef 
mothers milk helps boost a babys immunity and eliminates the 
need to use possibly contaminated water to prepare formula or other 
food 
un officials estimate that 4 million to 5 million children 
could be saved each year if they had been breastfed many deaths 
are caused by severe diarrhea infections 
an assistant directorgeneral of who hu chingli decried the 
situation in some poor countries in which companies provide baby 
formula free to new mothers who are capable of breastfeeding 
after beginning to bottlefeed her child in the hospital or clinic 
the mother continues to do so after going home but often does not 
have the money to buy the proper formula hu said 
such marketing violates a marketing code adopted by who in 1979 
un officials say only a few countries adhere to the code 
unicefs executive director james p grant said he hopes more 
nations will pledge to adopt the code when their leaders attend the 
world summit for children at the united nations in new york in 
september 
two formula makers carnation co a subsidiary of nestle and 
gerber which is producing a formula with bristolmyers have 
marketed their products directly to the public despite the 
objections of the academy which represents 39000 pediatricians 
however a spokesman said carnations marketing campaign which 
involved a few weeks of general consumer ads in the united 
states had been discontinued about 18 months ago 
he said the company did not consider that campaign to be direct 
marketing because the company was not identified in publicity 
promoting the use of infant formula we do not now nor have we 
directmarketed said dick curd a spokesman at carnation 
headquarters in los angeles 
nestle has been the target of a us consumer boycott for a 
decade because of its marketing of infant formulas in developing 
nations american home products another formulamaker marketing in 
developing nations also is being boycotted said howard bozich 
executive director of action for corporate accountability which 
monitors infantformula abuses 
eighteen other companies some from western europe and japan 
also sell formula in poor nations in violation of the who code he 
said 
the boycott against nestle ended after the company agreed in 
1984 to follow un marketing guidelines but it was renewed in 
1988 when consumer activists accused nestle of skirting the intent 
of the guidelines by encouraging some new mothers in developing 
countries to use formula even if they could breastfeed the 
company denied that charge 
who officials said the benefits of breastfeeding are so great 
that even mothers who tested positive during pregnancy for the hiv 
virus should nurse their children 
hu a chinese physician said the recommendation was based on 
research in many countries including those where there is a very 
high prevalence of aids when pressed he declined to elaborate 
saying the research included unpublished studies 
there have been cases of mothers apparently transmitting the hiv 
virus which causes aids to children through breast milk but it 
is rare and has not been used as a reason to discourage 
breastfeeding 
a study in june 1989 in the new england journal of medicine 
presented circumstantial evidence that breastfeeding may increase 
the aids risk for newborns the study directed by dr stephane 
blanche of necker hospital in paris found that among infected 
mothers aids infections were found in five of six infants who were 
breastfed compared with 25 of 99 who were not 
it cautioned that further studies are necessary before infants 
at risk in developing countries are deprived of the advantages of 
breastfeeding 
in the united states breastfeeding has declined about 1 
percent a year the past decade said dr antoinette eaton vice 
president of the american academy of pediatrics she said 
statistics show less than half of all mothers are still nursing 
their babies one month after birth 
</TEXT>
