<TEXT>
a judges ruling that forbade a woman 
from changing her last name without her husbands permission has 
been overturned 
however the superior court decision stopped short of barring 
the probate judge who issued the original ruling from doing so in 
the future 
the reversal is not surprising said steve brown 
executive director of rhode islands american civil liberties 
union superior court judge antonio almeida has simply recognized 
the very basic if obvious principle that women are no longer the 
chattel of their husbands 
im happy in one way but im uphappy because if another 
woman goes into his courtroom its possible that he could do 
this again lucille ann riccitelli said wednesday 
riccitelli 41 decided to resume using her maiden name when her 
father died suddenly with no sons her sister uses a hyphenated 
name she said 
she changed the name on her drivers license social security 
card and a bank account 
but fleet national bank refused to change the name on the bank 
account riccitelli held jointly with her mother without a court 
document substantiating the name change she said 
when probate court judge anthony b sciarretta learned 
riccitelli was married he told her to get her husbands consent 
she refused and he denied the namechange petition 
in march riccitelli represented by an aclu attorney appealed 
the ruling and also asked that sciarretta be forbidden from 
requiring a husbands permission in any future cases 
almeida in a brief opinion written friday and released 
wednesday formally changed riccitellis name 
under common law individuals have a right to change their 
name provided they do so with a nonfraudulent purpose almeida 
wrote since no fraudulent purpose exists on the part of the 
appellant the probate courts denial of said petition was in error 
and is hereby reversed 
he denied the motion preventing sciarretta from requiring a 
husbands consent in the future 
we are disappointed the judge did not go further brown 
said however i am hopeful that this will prompt judge 
sciarretta to rethink his anachronistic ways otherwise we will 
find ourselves back in court seeking future remedies 
sciarretta could not be reached for comment wednesday he was 
not at his home or office 
he said previously that he has a firm policy when there are 
family situations 
he said he feels spousal consent is needed if there is to be 
any integrity in the family unit 
riccitelli said the experience in which she was made to feel 
like a little girl has made her more aware of discrimination 
against women 
its a form of harassment that happened that opened my eyes in 
some ways she said i am really definitely more aware of 
things like that and i am willing to stand up for things much more 
easily 
