begin a fiveweek vacation on campaign finance reforms but they 
acknowledged that it might not happen because of widespread discord 
among democrats over its measures 
unlike their party colleagues in the senate house democrasts 
rejected calls to ban pacs which have overwhelmingly favored them 
over republicans in recent elections many also have voiced 
opposition that the proposed 550000 spending cap for house races 
is to low to cover both primary and general election challenges 
the senate bill would establish populationbased spending caps 
ranging from just under 2 million for senate candidates in the 
smallest states up to nearly 10 million for the largest 
california 
republicans called it a partisan charade to prevent 
republican challengers from raising enough money to overcome 
democratic incumbents name recognition advantage and deny the gop 
a chance to gain control of congress 
in my view the die is cast on this bill said senate gop 
leader bob dole of kansas expressing only scant optimism that 
maybe something will come out of all this unless theres some 
changes thats not going to be possible 
the bill would represent the first major change in election laws 
since congress passed the 1974 federal election campaign act in 
response to the watergate scandal and the resignation of president 
nixon because of it 
that law established both a taxpayer checkoff public financing 
mechanism and voluntary spending ceilings for presidential 
elections it also set spending ceilings on congressional races but 
they were overturned two years later by the supreme court as 
unconstitutional 
the senate bill would close loopholes in the 1974 law that 
allowed millionaires to make contributions in blocks of 100000 
through unregulated state party organizations to the campaigns of 
both bush and democrat michael dukakis in the last presidential 
election 
republicans after losing partyline votes to stop the practice 
said it still allows unions to spend millions of dollars of their 
members dues on voter registration and turnout 90 percent of it 
on behalf of democrats 
this campaign reform bill only reforms republicans 
complained dole we like reform but we dont want all of it 
its got to be shared 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the measures chances also were complicated as the senate began 
piling other amendments onto it some of them likely to virtually 
eliminate any chance of twothirds vetoproof support 
for example after voting to give up the 27337 in honoraria 
they can now pocket the senate barely approved 5149 new york 
sen daniel moynihans proposal requiring members to forgo unearned 
income of more than 15 percent of their regular salaries 
that would be a hard blow to the senates many millionaires 
whose stock and interest incomes far exceed their government 
paychecks and had little problem voting to ban honoraria 
sen robert c byrd dwva said members of the senate 
himself among them had supplemented their salaries with more than 
9 million in honoraria over the past decade 
the scandals of the past two years have put a black mark on 
public service and raised public cynicism to an alltime high 
byrd said were about at the level of used car salesmen in the 
publics esteem 
the senate voted last week to denounce sen david durenberger 
rminn for violating several ethics standards including skirting 
the limits on honoraria in a bookpublishing deal 
the house vote last year to give up its members honoraria also 
boosted their salaries to 124000 reluctant to vote itself the 
same 25 percent pay boost the senate instead retained the 
opportunity for its members to accept specialinterest fees 
in 1989 senators accepted nearly 3 million in honoraria and 
kept more than 21 million with the balance donated to charity 
according to their financial disclosure forms 
