<TEXT>
a federal judge wednesday rejected the 
countys plan to redraw voting districts calling it illogical and 
insensitive to minorities 
the ruling was issued by us district judge david kenyon who 
previously ruled that the layout of districts for the board of 
supervisors improperly deprived hispanics of political power in the 
nations most populous county 
kenyon ruled the board of supervisors conservative majority 
failed to redraw district boundaries 
he said the plan constitutes a nonsensical distortion of 
existing supervisorial districts a calloused interpretation of the 
voting rights act and is insensitive to the needs of hispanic and 
black residents 
the judge set a hearing for thursday to consider alternative 
plans proposed by civil rights groups and the us justice 
department the winners in a voting rights case against the county 
kenyon ruled june 7 the supervisors violated the federal voting 
rights act by conspiring in 1981 to draw district lines that 
preserved their incumbencies while diluting hispanic voting 
strength 
the lawsuit filed in august 1988 accused the supervisors of 
deliberately spreading the countys hispanic population across 
several districts when they changed voting boundaries after the 
1980 federal census 
though hispanics make up an estimated 35 percent of the countys 
87 million residents the fivemember board has not had an elected 
hispanic member in 115 years 
the boards conservatives responded to the ruling by drafting a 
plan that created a hispanic majority in one of the liberal board 
members districts while also preserving the conservative majority 
it was this plan that kenyon rejected wednesday 
attorney marc rosenbaum of the american civil liberties union 
one of the plaintiffs said the judges ruling sends a strong 
message to governments that think they can gerrymander away 
minority political clout 
their day is over said rosenbaum but those 
governmental bodies that respect the law adhere to the 
constitution and to the rights of minorities have nothing to 
fear 
the next redistricting plans to be submitted by the aclu the 
government and the mexican american legal defense and educational 
fund are aimed at creating a hispanic majority district but 
without an incumbent 
the plans could greatly increase hispanic political clout and 
overturn the conservative majority with possibly profound 
implications on future funding for such areas as health and social 
services programs 
conservative supervisor mike antonovich denounced the judges 
decision and vowed to fight it on appeal antonovich said the 
plaintiffs were simply trying to use the courts to upset the 
boards ideological complexion 
theyre doing that outside of the electoral process he said 
in defense of the current district boundaries antonovich 
pointed to the june election 
sarah flores a hispanic backed by conservative supervisors got 
the most votes for a seat opened by outgoing conservative 
supervisor peter schabarum and forced a runoff with superior court 
judge gregory obrien 
but plaintiffs have rejected antonovichs reasoning saying the 
ethnicity of a supervisor is not as important as who elects the 
supervisor kenyons decisions have put the outcome of the election 
in doubt 
</TEXT>
