<TEXT>
some editors are taking a close look at 
a doonesbury comic strip due out next week in which a character 
clad in nothing but rope utters provocative language 
frankly it didnt offend me but im thinking of all the 
people out there said jim hughes executive editor of the baton 
rouge morning advocate and state times 
the strip by gb trudeau features the character jj giving her 
rendition of performance art with a bucket over her head and 
nothing but rope covering her privates 
she speaks in fragmented sentences laced with words with sexual 
connotations such as lubricate and hot juices but doesnt 
make any direct reference to sex acts 
the way i read it its an attempt to show the lengths that 
the art community will go to thumb their noses at government 
grants said jack morrissey an associate editor at universal 
press syndicate the kansas city areabased company distributes the 
doonesbury strip to about 1000 newspapers 
trudeau appeared to be referring to controversy over national 
endowment of the arts funding some conservative politicians have 
tried to block government money going to artwork they consider 
obscene and several performance artists have lost their grants 
morrissey said several editors had called with questions about 
taste and the reason behind releasing the strip but no paper 
indicated that it would pull the comic next week he said 
hughes said he had his staff call other papers around the 
country wednesday to see whether they would run the strip which 
papers received this week and is scheduled for release from aug 6 
to aug 11 
hughes said his paper had yet to make a decision 
three of the papers contacted by hughes staff the kansas city 
star the los angeles times and the philadelphia inquirer said 
they examined the strip closely and decided to run it without 
alteration 
if you held it out the doonesbury people would get mad and 
if you run it i imagine some other people will get mad said joe 
mcguff vice president and editor of the star i just take that 
as a given 
bob duffy vice president of universal press said newspapers 
could choose to withhold the strip but he strongly discouraged 
editors from altering it for reasons of taste as papers have done 
to trudeaus comics in the past 
wed rather have them drop the strip than alter it he said 
thats always been our position but you cant police 1000 
newspapers 
