<TEXT>
at a park that was twice the worlds fair 
grounds amid softball games and bicycles under the vapor trails 
of thundering airliners hundreds convene each week to seek the 
virgin mary 
they are certain she is here in flushing meadows park they 
have assembled for 20 years since june 18 1970 when veronica 
lueken a housewife and mother of five first said she saw mary at 
a church in bayside queens 
the roman catholic church is not convinced but believers insist 
they are witnesses to a continuing miracle 
it increases our faith said kathy anderson a long island 
mother of four who attends with her husband a computer consultant 
we truly believe that jesus and the blessed mother are here this 
is the most important marian shrine of our day 
linda bonas 30 a brooklyn teacher looked around at the 500 or 
so worshippers reciting the rosary on a recent sunday and said 
if everything was happy and was doing well around the world you 
wouldnt have too many people here most of them realize theres 
something missing 
mrs lueken claims the apparitions tell her that unless we mend 
our sinning ways the world will be destroyed by comets 
earthquakes world war iii and other disasters 
but she rarely attends services she has had heart and 
gallbladder surgery and suffers from high blood pressure back pain 
and ringing in the ears her followers call her a victim soul 
one who suffers in exchange for blessings 
word of her first vision at st robert bellarmine roman catholic 
church spread quickly in 1975 she was barred from holding vigils 
there the crowds were too big 
police offered to let them meet at flushing meadows where the 
vatican pavilion stood during the 196465 worlds fair pope paul 
vi had blessed the site marked by a stone wall on a grassy field 
mrs lueken says the visions moved there from the church 
it seems an unlikely place for a miracle amid soccer and 
softball games joggers and bicyclists traffic drones from nearby 
expressways and jets roar overhead to and from la guardia airport 
sometimes drowning out the prayers 
worshippers bring a statue of the madonna each week and adorn it 
with roses the flowers believed blessed by the virgin during 
services are then given to the crowd 
frank derosa spokesman for the roman catholic diocese of 
brooklyn which oversees queens said no credibility can be given 
to the claims of apparitions at the site of the vigils the diocese 
does not believe that anything of an incredible or miraculous 
nature is happening there we discourage people from coming to 
attend the vigils 
michael mangan director of our lady of the roses mary help of 
mothers the official name for mrs luekens followers says the 
dioceses failure to certify the miracle is par for the course 
when it comes to the church and their involvement and assessment of 
apparitions 
he said the groups name came to mrs lueken in a message from 
mary 
roses as our lady explained is natures purest flower a 
symbol of perfection said mangan mary help of mothers is 
because many mothers are worried about their children today 
the group claims 60000 believers worldwide 
on a recent sunday peter livsack 63 came on a chartered bus 
from philadelphia like many others he brought a polaroid camera 
and snapped pictures of the madonna he said would become 
miraculous photos livsack says he often notices squiggles 
shadows and patches of light on the pictures when he gets home 
he believes these are messages from god resembling doves 
initials and faces of saints see the mouth see the eye right 
in the branches of the trees he asks 
many of the messages mrs lueken receives are predictions of 
doom gods punishment for mans rejection of him mangan 
says civilization has always been punished or ended when the 
moral decadence and sins has reached its peak 
but he added the virgin mary like a true mother has love 
for her children and shes coming to warn us to mend our ways and 
turn back to pray the holy rosary and practice the roman catholic 
faith 
mangan one of 15 fulltime employees says bills are paid 
through unsolicited donations requests for money are never 
made at the services and are not common in the groups literature 
our lady just gives enough to provide for her work he said 
the organization describes its history and mrs luekens 
messages in booklets videotapes radio and cable television shows 
aired around the country and even in advertisements on the subway 
were using the latest technology and modern means to 
propagate this message said mangan anything to inform these 
desperate souls out there 
