<DOCNO> AP900801-0212 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the products of the rocky flats nuclear 
weapons plant are euphemistically called triggers or pits 
but actually theyre the components for softballsize atomic 
bombs used to jumpstart the fusion reaction in a nuclear warhead 
rocky flats triggers go into the 25000 nuclear warheads in the 
united states arsenal the warheads which must be replaced 
periodically because plutonium decays are assembled at the pantex 
nuclear weapons plant in amarillo texas 
some of the plutonium used at rocky flats comes from aging 
nuclear warheads other plutonium comes from nuclear reactors 
at rocky flats high amounts of electricity or acid baths are 
used to melt or separate the plutonium from other elements the 
metal is packaged into disks which then are machined and formed 
into balls that become the heart of a nuclear weapon 
the actual shape of the trigger is a secret because some 
geometric shapes produce better explosions than others 
the triggers are shipped to texas where pantex workers attach 
highspeed explosives designed to detonate instantaneously causing 
an inward blast without simultaneous detonation the plutonium 
would simply explode scattering radiation but causing no atomic 
reaction 
the plutonium and explosives are placed near a core of hydrogen 
in an atomic explosion the plutonium undergoes fission its atoms 
splitting in a chain reaction that creates extremely high 
temperatures which ignite a source of neturons such as 
plutoniumberyllium the neutron source then sets off a combination 
of deuterium and tritium fusing hydrogen and setting off a 
reaction similar to that which powers the sun 
the power of a hydrogen warhead is measured in megatons the 
explosive force of a million tons of tnt 
the most modern us missiles carry several warheads of about a 
quarter to a half megaton each and some b52 bombs range up to 9 
megatons by contrast the total power of the bombs dropped on 
germany during world war ii totaled 13 megatons 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900801-0213 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
since it opened in 1951 the rocky flats 
nuclear weapons plant has been the scene of two major fires that 
allowed radioactivity to escape into the surrounding region 
no one knows how much but officials say they dont think the 
contamination was serious 
the most recent fire was on mothers day in 1969 
it began in a glove box used to handle highly radioactive 
plutonium and quickly spread to plutonium in other boxes 
firefighters contained the blaze but damage totaled 70 million 
the building in which it occurred is contaminated to 
infinity meaning radiation levels inside the building could not 
be calculated 
contamination outside the building was small officials say but 
the threat of widespread contamination was immense federal 
investigators concluded that only the heroic efforts of the 
firefighters prevented a complete loss of the building and its 
contents and a major release of plutonium into the environment 
with the city of denver only 16 miles away 
the investigation found heat detectors had been mistakenly 
insulated during remodeling and did not detect the fire until it 
was out of control 
a similar problem had occurred 12 years earlier when plant 
workers covered up heat detectors because they were frustrated by 
too many false alarms 
according to a report compiled by plant managers that fire on 
sept 11 1957 began in molds used to make plutonium detonators 
an explosion blew out 620 air filters allowing a cloud of 
radioactive waste to escape and drift toward denver 
the report said the radiation released was minimal although no 
determination ever was made on how much plutonium was missing 
officials say documentation on both fires is skimpy and they 
have no idea how much radiation was released the plants new 
manager egampg inc has set up teams to study records and try to 
determine how much radioactive material escaped 
</TEXT>
