<TEXT>
as the federal reserves antiinflation policy 
slows the economy to a crawl even a standstill and maybe a 
reversal the questions are becoming more numerous 
why for example do supporters of the feds goslow policy 
believe that growth beyond 25 percent a year is inflationary when 
it averaged nearly 4 percent a year with only 25 percent inflation 
in the 1950s and 1960s 
and when more recently japans economy has consistently grown 
by 45 percent to 5 percent a year without severe inflationary side 
effects 
why do they believe that inflation threatens when the factory 
operating rate approaches 84 percent of capacity when that was the 
norm in that same 20 year period 
why shouldnt growth be seen as the solution to economic 
problems rather than a creator of them doesnt experience show 
that sustained growth would reduce indebtedness at all levels 
raise exports increase income 
john wright has been among those questioners not just of recent 
policy but of the feds policies over many years he has written 
and lectured on the subject and has personally carried his views 
directly to the fed officials 
growth he says is not a dirty word this nations policy 
makers need to realize that growth is not only good it is also 
inherently noninflationary he says adding but one 
qualification 
so long as a reasonable share of it can be and is reinvested 
at reasonable capital costs in productive capacity 
that is so long as we the producers dont become just greedy 
consumers and eat up everything we grow but instead like good 
potato farmers put away some of the crop to continue seeding the 
farm 
wright is the founder of wright investors service a 
bridgeport conn firm operating internationally in money 
management financial advice and corporate and financial 
information 
in an address prepared for the american banker and bond buyer 
publications wright stated that again and again in the 1970s and 
80s the fed misread the causes of inflation and then tried 
remedies that badly damaged the economy 
inflation during those years was largely costpush wright 
said it was imported inflation pricefactors such as opec oil 
were its cause but the fed he said misread it as domestic 
demandpull inflation 
the latter inflation caused by demand that exceeded the 
economys capacity to produce is correctible by restricting the 
domestic money supply the fed did that for an inflation that 
simply didnt exist 
the result of these restrictions said wright were soaring 
interest rates and reduced production which further exacerbated 
rising product costs 
during this period the federal reserve boards failure to 
recognize the noninflationary growth potential of the us economy 
caused three significant recessions in the space of the 10 years 
19731982 he stated 
and with this result the lost national income and foregone 
federal tax revenues which resulted produced the 100 billion 
federal budget deficits which have plagued the us annually since 
1982 
wrights message to the fed please recognize that recession 
not inflation is the greater risk to the us economy ease 
monetary policy do so quickly and significantly breaking with the 
toolittletoolate fed tradition 
my prescription for the ailing us economy is much lower 
interest rates wright said lower rates he said would spur 
growth particularly for capital investments in plants and 
equipment 
the fed fears lower rates would spur inflationary demand wright 
says they underestimate the economys potential 
increased investment he reminds the fed could mean expanded 
supply as well as expanded demand the productionconsumption 
balance could be maintained and inflation restrained 
the economy could grow jobs could be created exports spurred 
the balance of payments improved tax revenues enhanced and debts 
repaid 
