<TEXT>
scientists say they have taken another 
step toward designer pigs for healthconscious consumers by 
creating lean pork with less saturated fat than todays cuts 
the key is the diet of hogs who are fed whole soybeans cooked 
in a special processor known as an extruder said scientists at the 
university of illinois and the harlan e moore heart research 
foundation 
the unusual feed ingredient produced pork with a significantly 
higher ratio of polyunsaturated to saturated fat a 50 percent 
improvement in pork chops and a 100 percent improvement in bacon 
we can produce healthier pork and do it in an economical 
way said dennis leszczynski a dietician and food scientist at 
the heart foundation in champaign and there are no important 
differences in animal performance meat taste texture processing 
or storage 
peter bechtel a university of illinois meat scientist who 
worked with leszczynski on the project prepared a report on the 
findings for todays meeting of the american society of animal 
science in ames iowa 
pigs are like humans were all a product of the kind of fat 
we eat bechtel said so we change the ratio of 
polyunsaturated fat in the pork by altering the fat that goes in 
the hogs 
because the final product may cost more to produce the 
researchers said farmers must sell processors and consumers on the 
health value of their new pork to justify a higher price 
leszczynski said farmers have had few incentives to deliver a 
leaner hog to market the price often has been based only on live 
weight bechtel said some processors now are paying a premium to 
farmers who deliver lean pigs 
the key is testing the market to see how much the consumer is 
willing to pay for healthier pork said leszczynski 
the american heart association says the ratio of polyunsaturated 
fat to saturated fat should be 1to1 said leszczynski he said 
feeding extruded soybeans improved the ratio from 28to1 to 
43to1 in pork chops and from 25to1 to 50to1 in bacon 
though the pork ration improved it still is not the 83to1 
ratio found in a lean chicken breast 
were getting closer leszczynski said the challenge now 
is to see how much higher we can go without adversely affecting the 
meat quality or the economics 
the study involved 160 pigs some had a diet that included 20 
percent extruded soubeans for the six weeks before slaughter 
conventional hog rations contain corn and soybean meal the 
scientists substituted the extruded whole soybeans for the meal in 
an effort to retain soy oil which is relatively high in 
polyunsaturated fat 
research at the international soybean program at the university 
of illinois has shown that extrusion not only leaves the oil in the 
final product but that it also destroys the natural digestive 
inhibitors in soybeans 
bechtel said most illinois farmers already have soybeans an 
extruder could cost about 8000 and could be shared by a group of 
farmers 
why couldnt a farmer take his soybeans have a little 
extruder and feed them directly to his pigs instead of selling the 
beans to a processor and buying back the meal bechtel said 
producing this kind of pork is an economic possibility 
some pork producers already deliver leaner animals to market by 
selecting breeds with less fat and by slaughtering them before they 
get too heavy that process has created pork cuts that are 97 
percent lean 
bechtel said his project indicated the composition of the 
remaining fat could be improved 
now were talking about custommade pork designer pigs he 
said they wont all be alike anymore 
</TEXT>
