<TEXT>
federal safety officials insist that the exxon 
valdez captain was drunk at the time of the alaskan oil spill they 
also blame his third mate the company that hired them the coast 
guard and port authorities for the disaster 
despite capt joseph hazelwoods acquittal by an alaskan jury 
and the coast guards dismissal last week of drunkenness charges 
against him the national transportation safety board said tuesday 
that his drinking was part of the probable cause of the nations 
worst oil spill 
board members said the coast guard needs to develop a more 
efficient system to monitor and control boat traffic in critical 
areas 
one of the lessons of this accident is that if we had a good 
vessel traffic system it probably would not have happened said 
board member jim burnett the same or worse results are possible 
in one of our other ports i think its a tragedy that weve had 
this wholesale neglect of the vessel traffic system 
but the board also cited exxon corp for failing to provide its 
biggest oil tanker with a fit master and a rested and sufficient 
crew 
and it said third mate gregory cousins failed to properly 
maneuver the vessel after he was left at the helm the coast guard 
failed to control traffic in the iceclogged sound and the state of 
alaska failed to provide an effective pilots service to guide 
ships out of the sound 
the board voted 40 to adopt the fivepart probable cause and a 
long list of conclusions and recommendations resulting from the 
march 29 1989 spill of 11 million gallons into prince william 
sound 
the probable cause reflects the decision of the board that in 
addition to the alcohol impairment of the ships master there are 
safety issues of equal importance said burnett 
board chairman james kolstad said the ntsb hopes its report 
which included 36 safety recommendations will help prevent future 
spills 
the boards analyses carry no force of law and by statute 
cannot be used in court cases but they often serves as guidelines 
for congressional administrative and private action 
hazelwoods lawyer thomas russo said the safety board members 
acted like they dropped off the moon in again accusing 
hazelwood of being drunk twentyone witnesses at hazelwoods trial 
testified that he was sober russo said and authorities botched 
the blood tests showing alcohol in his system more than 10 hours 
after the accident 
their conclusions are not founded in the evidence russo 
said 
the board said eyewitnesses medical tests and an unusual study 
of hazelwoods speech indicated he was drunk when the ship ran 
aground 
medical investigator merritt birky said calculations based on 
blood tests of hazelwood show that he would have had a blood 
alcohol content of 2 percent at the time of the grounding which 
is five times the legal intoxication level under coast guard rules 
birky said he believes hazelwoods alcohol level shows he 
probably was drinking on board which is against exxon rules 
hazelwood denies drinking on board although he has admitted 
drinking prior to boarding the vessel 
he is appealing a conviction in alaska of one misdemeanor charge 
of negligent discharge of oil for which he was fined 50000 and 
ordered to spend 1000 hours cleaning alaskan beaches 
last week the coast guard dismissed charges of drunkenness and 
misconduct against hazelwood but suspended his license as a ships 
master for nine months after he pleaded no contest to breaking 
rules involving drinking alcohol prior to duty and leaving the 
bridge 
this is the largest and costliest accident the safety board 
has ever investigated kolstad said in opening the meeting he 
said 2 billion had been spent cleaning up the spill 
investigators also raised concerns about hazelwoods attempts to 
move the vessel off the reef as it was spilling oil saying it 
could have caused greater problems 
he was going into an unknown area where he couldnt have known 
whether it would remain upright or capsize said chief 
investigator william woody 
