<TEXT>
vacationers bound for summer getaways will notice something has 
happened to outoftheway tourist spots many have become 
miniature shopping meccas catering to devoted bargain seekers 
clusters of shops carrying discounted designer duds have 
sprouted up all over the country more manufacturers whose wares 
are normally peddled by mainstream retailers are striking out on 
their own 
outlet complexes are thriving in areas frequented by tourists 
who have the time to browse for good buys busloads of pricewise 
shoppers regularly pour in elsewhere outlets grouped near major 
thoroughfares are catching the attention of passersby 
the trend has ominous implications for traditional retailing it 
wont run all regular stores out of business but it does mean more 
competition in a saturated industry already fraught with fierce 
battling for market share 
sales at outlets are growing faster than general retail 
revenues although they still account for a small portion of 
retailing 
outlets generated nearly 6 billion in sales last year 
according to value retail news a clearwater flabased 
publication that tracks the industry by contrast a single 
retailer industry biggie sears roebuck and co alone had 1989 
sales of over 30 billion 
people like the excitement of shopping in a factory outlet 
they like the prices says lynn ellsworth president of company 
stores development corp a brentwood tennbased builder of 
outlet malls and a pioneer in the field 
manufacturers have several incentives to sell directly to 
consumers it allows them to control the process of getting rid of 
leftovers rather than risk problems that can crop up when they 
unload merchandise on liquidators 
closeout chains and offprice merchants which absorb excess 
apparel and sell it at discount often compete for customers with 
nearby department stores and other regular retailers 
manufacturers usually make sure their own outlets are far away 
from major shopping hubs so they dont jeopardize sales of their 
labels selling at fullprice stores or upset relations with 
retailers their primary customers 
we purposely stay away from traditional retailers notes 
benard holtzman president of apparel designer harve benard ltd 
clothing companies accessory makers and others that go into 
retailing must tred carefully the last thing they want is for 
outlet customers to return home gloating to their local retailer 
about the great deal they got 
womens apparel powerhouse liz claiborne inc has located its 22 
outlet stores 45 minutes to an hour away from regular retailers 
selling its label 
ritzy ralph laurens lines are sold at discount outlets 
deliberately situated 90 miles to 120 miles away from places where 
the polo collection is sold in fullprice companyowned boutiques 
and department stores 
nevertheless the issue is so touchy that manufacturers dont 
exactly go out of their way to publicize their involvement in the 
outlet business some even disguise their name meaning customers 
cant tell who owns an outlet pricy izodlacoste sportswear is 
sold at outlets called fashion flair for instance 
irked by the trend the national shoe retailers association 
recently adopted a resolution expressing disapproval of the 
proliferation of companyowned factory outlets independent shoe 
retailers are up in arms because they say manufacturers are 
bypassing them in channeling merchandise to outlets 
association president bill boettge said the group believes 
independent shoe sellers are being treated unfairly he said the 
group isnt trying to start a national boycott but some association 
members are refusing to carry merchandise of manufacturers that 
operate their own outlets 
from a manufacturers point of view it makes good business 
sense to look for new channels of distribution upheaval in the 
retail industry intensifed by the bankruptcy filings of big name 
chains including the parent companies of bloomingdales the bon 
marche lazarus and others has made manufacturers nervous about 
depending on department stores to market merchandise 
no longer mere havens for fashion hasbeens manufacturers 
increasingly use their factory outlets to showcase merchandise 
phillipsvan heusen corp reportedly does half its business in 
its own outlets marketing van heusen shirts and shoes from its 
gh bass amp co division 
commercial developers say projects involving outlets tend to get 
financial backing more easily in these tight money days than 
construction of traditional retail centers 
although lenders have tightened up their practices after the 
savings and loan debacle theyre still willing to support sound 
deals conventional retailers may be on the ropes but factory 
outlets look like theyre on stable ground according to richard 
echikson chairman of millburn njbased retail consultants inc 
which helps clients assess potential retail investments 
there is an increasing interest in the financial community and 
development community in true factory outlet malls says echikson 
with financial backing an increasing number of outlets has gone 
upscale offering entertainment and other amenities the woodbury 
common in central valley ny for instance recreates a village 
setting 
malls are growing bigger too benderson development co out of 
buffalo ny plans to open what it claims will be the worlds 
largest manufacturers outlet mall late next year in downtown 
niagara falls 
not all outlets are in the middle of nowhere or even near prime 
tourist attractions many outlets have been moving closer to 
metropolitan areas as more manufacturers get into the act 
according to value retail news the number of outlet chains has 
mushroomed and last year more were opened than ever before in a 
single year by the middle of this year there were about 350 
chains in operation up from 264 at the start of 1989 
the popularity is expected to continue as consumers save more of 
their incomes than they did during the freespending 80s aging 
baby boomers are keen on bargains now that they are tucking away 
spare dollars for their tots educations 
charles bloom chairman of the chelsea group a new jerseybased 
developer owner and operator of factory outlet shopping centers 
says the concept complements traditional retailing and will never 
supplant it 
without retail there is no wholesale he notes you 
couldnt buy a bargain if it wasnt selling for a higher price 
somewhere else 
</TEXT>
