karsten mahlmann chairman of the chicago board 
of trade said today he has resigned as head of a financially 
battered commodities firm that operates a subsidiary accused of 
violating the commodity exchange act 
in a letter to members of the board of trade mahlmann said his 
resignation as chairman of stotler group and stotler and co was 
effective at noon tuesday 
mahlmann said he has no plans to step down as chairman of the 
board of trade 
in the letter he said he simply was not a party to the 
financial decisions at stotler which are now being scrutinized by 
the exchange and the regulators 
i have had no daytoday management responsibilities at 
stotler since early 1988 and my position at stotler was 
constantly eroded mahlmann said 
mahlmann said had he been aware of stotlers recent financial 
decisions i would not have condoned them and i would have taken 
action to reverse them 
he said he remains stotler groups largest shareholder 
his resignation comes a day after federal regulators filed a 
civil complaint accusing a stotler subsidiary of violating the 
commodity exchange act 
filed in us district court by the commodity futures trading 
commission the complaint names stotler funds inc a commodity 
pool operator owned by stotler group 
stotler and co a futures brokerage and the groups principal 
subsidiary has withdrawn from the futures business because of 
shaky finances 
in its complaint the government said stotler funds improperly 
used pools of clients money which had been set up for investing in 
commodity futures contracts 
the cftc said stotler funds instead used about 80 percent of one 
pools assets about 455 million to invest in stotler group 
in addition stotler funds lent 1 million from another pool to its 
parent company 
stotler funds use of pool assets in this way operated as a 
fraud or deceit on clients or participants in violation of the 
commodity exchange act the regulators contended 
the complaint seeks a court order to stop these practices and 
the appointment of a temporary equity receiver 
the chicago tribune reported that hundreds of investors in the 
pools called compass and advanced portfolio management were 
notified monday in a letter from stotler that the holding company 
had defaulted on the two deals and that henceforth the two pools 
no longer would do business with the parent 
in a letter from thomas kolter stotler groups general counsel 
participants in apm and compass also were told that because of the 
defaults the investors wouldnt be allowed to redeem their shares 
in the pools for the time being the tribune reported 
mahlmann and stotler officials did not return telephone calls 
today 
meanwhile the board of trade announced that its board of 
directors had voted to give mahlmann a vote of confidence as 
chairman of the exchange despite the problems with his futures 
brokerage 
in recognition of his commitment to the board of trade the 
board of directors fully and unanimously expressed its confidence 
in karsten mahlmann as chairman the exchange said in a statement 
outlining action take at a special meeting monday 
it said the special session was called so that the board could 
be briefed by the exchanges business conduct committee which has 
been reviewing the situation with stotler 
